const a = [
  {"id":3566,"text":"A 13-year-old female presents to the outpatient department (OPD) with on and off menorrhagia, bleeding gums, and petechial rashes. Her laboratory reports show the following results; Hb= 12.5 g/dl, platelet count= 350,000/mm3, activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)= 49s (normal: 29-40s). Which of the following could be the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The likely diagnosis for the 13-year-old female with on and off **menorrhagia, bleeding gums**, and **petechial rashes**, along with an **elevated activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT)**, is **von Willebrand disease**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand disease is a bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of **von Willebrand factor (vWF)**, a protein involved in platelet adhesion and clot formation. The symptoms often include mucocutaneous bleeding, such as nosebleeds, easy bruising, heavy or prolonged menstrual bleeding, and bleeding gums.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the normal platelet count and hemoglobin level make iron deficiency anemia less likely as a diagnosis. Anemia of chronic disease is also less likely as it typically presents with lower hemoglobin levels. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) typically presents with isolated thrombocytopenia and does not cause prolonged aPTT. Thrombotic microangiopathy usually presents with signs of microvascular thrombosis and associated organ damage, which are not described in this case.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662.","responses":[{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"von Willebrand disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombotic microangiopathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia of chronic disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3625,"text":"Which of the following statement is correct regarding folic acid and vitamin B12?","explanation":"**Vitamin B12** is essential for the formation of the **active form of folic acid**.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 plays a critical role in the conversion of folic acid into its active form, known as methyltetrahydrofolate (MTHF). Without sufficient vitamin B12, folic acid cannot be properly utilized by the body. This conversion is necessary for various cellular processes, including DNA synthesis, red blood cell production, and nervous system function.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B12 alone takes part in DNA synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 plays a role in purine synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid is essential for the formation of the active form of vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 is essential for the formation of the active form of folic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid plays a role in pyrimidine synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3774,"text":"Where does red infarct usually occur in?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Robbins SL, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 9th ed. Elsevier/Saunders; 2013: 131.","responses":[{"text":"Venous occlusion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arterial occlusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3776,"text":"Which of the following is covered by pseudostratified columnar epithelium?","explanation":"The structure that is covered by **pseudostratified columnar epithelium** is the **pharyngeal tonsil**. Pseudostratified columnar epithelium is commonly found in the respiratory tract, including the lining of the pharynx (throat). The lingual tonsil, palatine tonsil, spleen, and lymph nodes do not have a lining of pseudostratified columnar epithelium.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 281.","responses":[{"text":"Pharyngeal tonsil","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lingual tonsil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Palatine tonsil","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3787,"text":"What are the substrates of heme synthesis?","explanation":"The substrates of heme synthesis are **succinyl CoA** and **glycine**. **Heme synthesis** involves a series of enzymatic reactions that utilize succinyl CoA, derived from the citric acid cycle, and glycine as the primary building blocks for heme production. These substrates are converted into porphyrin, which is then further modified to form heme. Acetyl CoA and valine are not directly involved in heme synthesis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 443.","responses":[{"text":"Succinyl CoA and glycine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetyl CoA and valine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetyl CoA and glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Succinyl CoA and valine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Valine and glycine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":3974,"text":"Extracellular hemoglobin is bound to a plasma protein in order to avoid loss of hemoglobin in urine. Which plasma protein binds free hemoglobin?","explanation":"The plasma protein that binds **free hemoglobin** is **haptoglobin**. Haptoglobin is an **α-2-globulin** protein produced by the liver. Its primary function is to bind free hemoglobin released from ruptured red blood cells (RBCs) and prevent its loss in the urine. Haptoglobin forms a complex with hemoglobin, and this complex is then removed from circulation by macrophages in the reticuloendothelial system, primarily in the liver.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 475.","responses":[{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasminogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Haptoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepcidin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4014,"text":"A 5-year-old boy comes to the outpatient department complaining of a painful and swollen knee. On examination, bleeding is seen within the knee joint but with no signs of physical trauma. His mother gives a family history of a maternal uncle who recently died of a bleeding disorder. Investigations show isolated increased APTT. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hemophilia A** is an X-linked recessive disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of coagulation factor VIII.\r\n\r\nThe clinical presentation of a painful and swollen joint without a history of physical trauma suggests an intra-articular hemorrhage. Hemophilia A leads to impaired blood clotting, specifically due to a deficiency of factor VIII, which is involved in the intrinsic pathway of coagulation. As a result, patients with hemophilia A are prone to prolonged APTT (activated partial thromboplastin time).\r\n\r\nThe X-linked inheritance pattern explains the family history of a maternal uncle with a bleeding disorder. Hemophilia A predominantly affects males, while females are usually carriers of the disease.\r\n\r\nConfirmatory laboratory tests may include specific assays to measure factor VIII activity or genetic testing to identify mutations in the factor VIII gene.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 662-663.","responses":[{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic uremic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4219,"text":"In hemoglobin S (HbS), which amino acid residue is substituted by valine at the sixth position of the beta-globin chain?","explanation":"In **hemoglobin S (HbS)**, the amino acid residue that is substituted by valine at the sixth position of the beta-globin chain is **glutamate**. This substitution results in the formation of abnormal hemoglobin that can polymerize and cause red blood cells to sickle in certain conditions, leading to **sickle cell disease**.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 635.","responses":[{"text":"Tyrosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isoleucine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4265,"text":"The clot is failing to retract. Defect in which of the following would be the likely cause?","explanation":"**Clot retraction** is primarily a function of **platelets**. Platelets play a crucial role in the process of clot retraction, where they contract and pull the edges of the wound closer together, reducing the size of the clot. Platelet contraction is mediated by actin and myosin interactions within the platelets. Defects in platelet function or number can impair clot retraction and lead to inadequate wound healing.","reference":"Jansen EE, Hartmann M. Clot retraction: cellular mechanisms and inhibitors, measuring methods, and clinical implications. Biomedicines. Published August 21, 2021. Accessed June 4, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8394358/","responses":[{"text":"Platelets","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4470,"text":"What does heparin activate?","explanation":"**Heparin** activates **antithrombin III (AT III)**. Heparin binds to AT III and enhances its ability to inactivate several coagulation factors, including thrombin (Factor IIa) and Factors IXa, Xa, XIa, and XIIa. By accelerating the inhibitory action of AT III, heparin helps to regulate and inhibit the clotting process.","reference":"Katzung BG, Kruidering-Hall M, Trevor AJ. Katzung \u0026 Trevor’s Pharmacology Examination \u0026 Board Review. 12th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 285-286.","responses":[{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":4479,"text":"Which of the following agents directly activates plasminogen?","explanation":"**Urokinase** is the agent that **directly activates plasminogen**. Urokinase is a naturally occurring enzyme that is involved in the breakdown of blood clots. It directly converts plasminogen into plasmin, which then breaks down fibrin in the clot. Urokinase has been used therapeutically as a thrombolytic agent to dissolve blood clots in conditions such as deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017.","responses":[{"text":"Streptokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue plasminogen activator (tPA)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urokinase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":4490,"text":"Protein C and S are involved in which of the following?","explanation":"**Protein C and S** are involved in the **cleavage of clotting factors**. They are part of the anticoagulant system and function to regulate and inhibit the clotting process. Protein C acts as a natural anticoagulant by inactivating factors Va and VIIIa, which are involved in the clotting cascade. Protein S serves as a cofactor for protein C in its anticoagulant activity. Together, protein C and S help to maintain the balance between clotting and anticoagulation, preventing excessive clot formation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Cleavage of clotting factors","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enhancing chemotaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreasing bleeding time","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinolysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10026,"text":"In case of an injury, a deficiency of which of the following would impair the adhesion of platelets to the subendothelial collagen?","explanation":"In the process of hemostasis, adhesion of platelets to the subendothelial collagen is a crucial step in forming a platelet plug to prevent bleeding. The key molecule involved in this adhesion is **von Willebrand factor (vWF)**.\r\n\r\nVon Willebrand factor is a multimeric glycoprotein synthesized by endothelial cells and megakaryocytes. It plays a critical role in mediating platelet adhesion by binding to both the exposed collagen at the site of injury and the platelet surface receptor, glycoprotein Ib (GPIb). This interaction between vWF and GPIb allows platelets to adhere to the damaged vessel wall and initiate the formation of a platelet plug.\r\n\r\nDeficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor can lead to a bleeding disorder known as von Willebrand disease, characterized by impaired platelet adhesion and defective clot formation. Without adequate von Willebrand factor, platelets are unable to adhere effectively to the subendothelial collagen, resulting in impaired hemostasis and prolonged bleeding.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 116.","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinogen stabilizing factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand factor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10054,"text":"Which of the following is not an example of an antibody-mediated response?","explanation":"**Graft-versus-host disease (GVHD)** is an immune reaction that occurs when immunocompetent cells from a graft (such as bone marrow or stem cells) recognize the recipient's tissues as foreign and mount an attack. In GVHD, the donor T cells attack the recipient's tissues, leading to tissue damage and inflammation. This immune response is primarily cell-mediated and involves the activation of T cells, rather than the production of antibodies by B cells.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, **drug-induced hemolytic anemia, blood transfusion reactions, Rh incompatibility at birth, and autoimmune diseases** are examples of antibody-mediated responses. These conditions involve the production of antibodies by B cells that recognize and target specific antigens, leading to tissue damage, destruction of red blood cells, or inflammation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 239.","responses":[{"text":"Rh incompatibility at birth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug-induced hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Graft-versus-host disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood transfusion reaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10076,"text":"Which of the following is not an antibody-mediated disease?","explanation":"**Hemophilia** is not an antibody-mediated disease. Hemophilia is a **genetic disorder** characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of clotting factors, specifically **factor VIII (hemophilia A) or factor IX (hemophilia B)**. It is not caused by antibodies targeting specific antigens. In hemophilia, the clotting process is impaired, leading to prolonged bleeding and difficulty in forming blood clots. Antibody-mediated diseases involve an immune response where antibodies are produced and target specific antigens, leading to tissue damage or dysfunction. Examples of antibody-mediated diseases include hemolytic anemia, urticaria (hives), and immune thrombocytopenia (ITP). Asthma, on the other hand, is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways and is not primarily antibody-mediated, although it does involve immune system activation.","reference":"Justiz Vaillant AA, Vashisht R, Zito PM. Immediate hypersensitivity reactions. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed June 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513315/","responses":[{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenia (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urticaria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11722,"text":"The red pulp of the spleen contains which one of the following?","explanation":"The spleen is divided into two main compartments: the **red pulp** and the **white pulp**. The **red pulp** is responsible for filtering and processing blood, while the **white pulp** is involved in immune responses.\r\n\r\nWithin the red pulp, there are **sinusoids** and **cords of Billroth**. The sinusoids are vascular channels lined by endothelial cells and are involved in the filtration of blood. The cords of Billroth are reticular tissue structures that contain macrophages, lymphocytes, plasma cells, and erythrocytes. These cords help to remove damaged or old red blood cells, as well as pathogens and cellular debris, from the circulation.\r\n\r\nThe white pulp of the spleen is primarily composed of periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths (PALS) surrounding central arterioles. The PALS contain T-lymphocytes and are involved in initiating immune responses to antigens.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 286.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cords of bilroth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Central arteriole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"PALS (periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11771,"text":"A girl is brought to the outpatient department with complaints of gum bleeding, and epistaxis. Her complete blood count (CBC) shows a normal platelet count and prolonged bleeding time. There is a family history of a younger sister with easy bruising. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"This girl with gum bleeding, epistaxis, normal platelet count, prolonged bleeding time, and a family history of a younger sister with easy bruising most likely has **Glanzmann thrombasthenia**.\r\n\r\n**Glanzmann thrombasthenia** is an inherited bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency or dysfunction of the platelet **glycoprotein IIb/IIIa** (integrin αIIbβ3), which is essential for **platelet aggregation**. In this condition, platelets are unable to bind fibrinogen and form stable platelet plugs, leading to impaired clot formation and increased bleeding tendency.\r\n\r\nThe normal platelet count in Glanzmann thrombasthenia distinguishes it from other platelet disorders associated with thrombocytopenia. The prolonged bleeding time is a result of the defective platelet function.\r\n\r\nThe family history of a younger sister with easy bruising suggests an inherited condition. Glanzmann thrombasthenia is an autosomal recessive disorder, meaning both parents are carriers of the mutated gene.\r\n\r\nThe other answer choices listed, such as drug-induced thrombocytopenia, hemophilia, immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP), and vitamin K deficiency, do not correlate with the presented clinical features and family history.","reference":"(1) Le T, Bhushan V. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2022. 32nd ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2022: 434.\r\n\r\n(2) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 660.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin K deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drug induced thrombocytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glanzmann thrombasthenia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11827,"text":"A 60-year-old patient comes to the clinic with pain in his leg for over a week. He further adds that due to pain, he could not move his leg. He has now developed deep vein thrombosis in his leg. Which of the following factors is most likely responsible for thrombus formation?","explanation":"The development of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in the leg of a 60-year-old patient is most likely due to immobilization. Immobilization refers to a state of limited or no physical movement, which can lead to blood stasis and an increased risk of thrombus formation.\r\n\r\nThe patient reports having pain in his leg for over a week, and due to the pain, he could not move his leg effectively. Immobility, especially when prolonged, can disrupt normal blood flow within the veins. Reduced muscle contraction and movement impede the normal pumping action of the calf muscles, which helps propel blood through the deep veins. This stagnant blood flow increases the risk of blood clot formation.\r\n\r\nWhile hyperglycemia and hypoglycemia are both metabolic conditions, they are not directly associated with the development of thrombosis. Surgery can increase the risk of DVT due to factors such as trauma to blood vessels and prolonged immobilization during the recovery period. However, in this case, immobilization itself is the most likely cause of the thrombus formation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 123.","responses":[{"text":"Hypoglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surgery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperglycemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immobilization","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":11843,"text":"A 5-year-old child, who has a history of eczema, develops rhinitis and develops asthma with seasonal change. What is the most likely change seen on the peripheral blood smear?","explanation":"The most likely change seen on the peripheral blood smear in a 5-year-old child with a history of eczema, rhinitis, and seasonal asthma is eosinophilic leukocytosis. Eosinophilic leukocytosis refers to an increased number of eosinophils in the blood.\r\n\r\nEczema, rhinitis, and asthma are commonly associated with allergic conditions. In allergic reactions, such as seasonal allergies, there is an activation of immune cells, particularly eosinophils. Eosinophils play a significant role in the allergic response, and their numbers increase in response to allergens.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the child's symptoms of rhinitis and asthma with seasonal changes suggest an allergic component to their condition. The presence of eczema further supports an underlying allergic tendency. When allergic reactions occur, eosinophils migrate to the affected tissues and can also be detected in the peripheral blood, resulting in eosinophilic leukocytosis.\r\n\r\nLymphocytosis refers to an increased number of lymphocytes in the blood. While lymphocytes play a role in the immune response, they are not specifically associated with the allergic component seen in this case.\r\n\r\nNeutrophilic leukocytosis refers to an increased number of neutrophils in the blood. Neutrophils are typically elevated in bacterial infections or other inflammatory conditions, but they are not directly associated with allergic reactions.\r\n\r\nMonocytosis refers to an increased number of monocytes in the blood. Monocytes are involved in the immune response against various pathogens, but they are not specifically related to the allergic manifestations described in the case.\r\n\r\nBasophilic leukocytosis refers to an increased number of basophils in the blood. Basophils are involved in allergic reactions, but they are not commonly seen in significant numbers in peripheral blood smears.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 584.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophilic leukocytosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilic leukocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophilic leukocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12532,"text":"A biopsy specimen of the thymus is examined under a microscope and many whorl-like corpuscles are observed. Which of the following statements coincides with the corpuscles mentioned earlier?","explanation":"The whorl-like corpuscles observed in the thymus are known as Hassall's corpuscles or thymic corpuscles. These corpuscles are a characteristic feature of the thymus and are composed of specialized **type VI epithelial reticular cells.**\r\n\r\nHassall's corpuscles are mainly found in the medulla (inner region) of the thymus. They are composed of concentric layers of flattened or squamous epithelial reticular cells, which are arranged in a whorl-like pattern.\r\n\r\nThe function of Hassall's corpuscles is not completely understood, but they are believed to play a role in the maturation of T-cells and the regulation of immune responses within the thymus.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that the composition and appearance of Hassall's corpuscles can vary, and they may also contain other cell types, such as macrophages and dendritic cells. However, the predominant component of these corpuscles is epithelial reticular cells, specifically type VI.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 7th ed. Paramount; 2021: 136.","responses":[{"text":"They have their embryological origin from mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are derived from T memory cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are frequently seen in thymus of young individuals","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"They are composed of epithelial reticular cells type VI","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"They are mainly located in the thymic cortex","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12533,"text":"Which of the following is a differentiating point between the lymph node and the thymus?","explanation":"A distinguishing feature between the lymph node and the thymus is that the thymus **lacks afferent lymphatics**. Lymph nodes are designed to filter lymph fluid via afferent lymphatic vessels and are integral to the adaptive immune response, whereas the thymus is a primary lymphoid organ where T lymphocyte maturation occurs and does not have afferent lymphatics because it does not perform filtration of lymph from peripheral tissues.\r\n\r\nThe thymus is derived from both the endoderm and the mesoderm (endoderm for the epithelial components and mesoderm for the connective tissue components). The thymus is indeed a primary lymphoid organ, not a secondary one. The thymus does have efferent lymphatics, through which mature T cells leave the thymus to enter the circulation.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 276.","responses":[{"text":"The thymus is a secondary lymphoid organ","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The thymus lacks afferent lymphatics","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The thymus lacks efferent lymphatics","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The thymus is derived from the mesoderm only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The thymus is derived from the endoderm only","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12534,"text":"A patient's blood reticulocyte count was increased after a blood loss during an accident. A reticulocyte is classified as which of the following?","explanation":"Reticulocytes are classified as immature erythrocytes. They are formed in the bone marrow from the precursor cells called erythroblasts. During the final stages of maturation, reticulocytes lose their nucleus and other organelles, becoming mature erythrocytes.\r\n\r\nThe reticulocyte count is a measure of the percentage of reticulocytes in the total red blood cell population. An increased reticulocyte count indicates an increased production of red blood cells, which can occur in response to conditions such as blood loss, hemolysis (breakdown of red blood cells), or increased erythropoietin production (a hormone that stimulates red blood cell production).\r\n\r\nReticulocytes are larger and contain residual ribosomal material, giving them a reticular or \"polka-dot\" appearance when stained. They are released into the bloodstream and mature into fully functional erythrocytes within a couple of days.\r\n\r\nMonitoring the reticulocyte count is important in assessing the bone marrow's response to various conditions affecting red blood cell production and turnover.","reference":"Siddiqui LH. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 7th ed. Paramount; 2021: 76.","responses":[{"text":"An erythrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"An immature erythrocyte","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A agranulocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A granulocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A mature erythrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12535,"text":"In which of the following splenic areas does the breakdown of the RBCs occur?","explanation":"The spleen is an important organ involved in the filtration and removal of old or damaged red blood cells from circulation. Within the spleen, the breakdown of RBCs primarily takes place in the red pulp.\r\n\r\nThe red pulp of the spleen is composed of a network of splenic cords and sinusoids. It serves as a reservoir for blood and contains various cell types, including macrophages. Macrophages in the red pulp play a crucial role in the phagocytosis and degradation of aged or damaged RBCs.\r\n\r\nWhen RBCs reach the red pulp, they come into contact with macrophages that remove them from circulation. The macrophages break down the RBCs, recycling components such as iron and globin, and eliminating waste products.\r\n\r\nThe white pulp of the spleen, on the other hand, is primarily involved in immune functions, such as the detection and response to pathogens.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 290.","responses":[{"text":"Red pulp","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"White pulp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic module","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malphigian corpuscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Periarteriolar lymphoid sheaths(PALS)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12536,"text":"Which of the following statements best defines the process of vasculogenesis?","explanation":"Vasculogenesis is a critical process during embryonic development that involves the formation of blood vessels from a specific population of mesodermal cells known as hemangioblasts. These hemangioblasts have the ability to differentiate into both hematopoietic (blood-forming) and endothelial (blood vessel-forming) lineages.\r\n\r\nDuring vasculogenesis, hemangioblasts aggregate and organize into blood islands, which are clusters of precursor cells. Within these blood islands, the precursor cells differentiate and give rise to endothelial cells, which form the inner lining of blood vessels, and hematopoietic cells, which give rise to blood cells.\r\n\r\nThe process of vasculogenesis is responsible for the initial establishment of the circulatory system, including the formation of major blood vessels and the primary capillary plexus. It is an essential step in the development of the embryo, ensuring the proper distribution of nutrients and oxygen to different tissues and organs.","reference":"Risau W, Flamme I. Vasculogenesis. Published 1995. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8689573/","responses":[{"text":"It is the arise of vessels from the heart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the arise of vessels from the subclavian artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the arise of vessels from the aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the arise of vessels from determined group of mesodermal cells(hemangioblasts)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is the arise of vessels from pre-existing vessels","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12538,"text":"Hemangioblasts are classified as which of the following?","explanation":"Hemangioblasts are a type of progenitor cell that have the ability to differentiate into both hematopoietic (blood-forming) and endothelial (blood vessel-forming) lineages. They are considered to be multipotent progenitor cells with the potential to give rise to various cell types involved in blood and vascular development.\r\n\r\nDuring embryonic development, hemangioblasts are derived from the mesoderm, which is one of the primary germ layers in the early embryo. Mesoderm gives rise to various tissues and structures including blood, blood vessels, connective tissues, and muscle.\r\n\r\nHemangioblasts play a critical role in the formation of blood islands, which are clusters of hematopoietic and endothelial cells that eventually develop into blood vessels and blood cells. These cells contribute to the development of the circulatory system and are involved in the production of both red and white blood cells.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 63.","responses":[{"text":"Ectodermal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Precursor cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endodermal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progenitor cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesodermal cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12539,"text":"Absorption of which of the following substance from the small intestine is prevented by hepcidin to avoid its accumulation in the blood?","explanation":"Hepcidin is a hormone produced by the liver that plays a crucial role in regulating iron metabolism in the body. It acts by inhibiting the absorption of dietary iron from the small intestine and by blocking iron release from iron-storing cells such as hepatocytes and macrophages.\r\n\r\nWhen iron levels in the body are high, hepcidin is released into the bloodstream. Hepcidin binds to ferroportin, a protein found on the surface of enterocytes (cells in the small intestine responsible for absorbing iron), macrophages, and hepatocytes. This binding triggers internalization and degradation of ferroportin, preventing the release of iron into the bloodstream and inhibiting its absorption from the gut.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting iron absorption, hepcidin helps prevent excessive accumulation of iron in the blood, which can be harmful due to its pro-oxidant properties. Hepcidin levels are regulated by various factors, including iron stores, erythropoietic activity, and inflammatory signals.","reference":"Ganz T. Hepcidin. [Rinsho Ketsueki] The Japanese Journal of Clinical Hematology. Published 2016. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27725588/","responses":[{"text":"Magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Folate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12540,"text":"Which of the following is the amount of hemoglobin present in 100 ml of red blood cells?","explanation":"Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin Concentration (MCHC) is a measure of the concentration of hemoglobin in a given volume of packed red blood cells. It is expressed as the amount of hemoglobin per 100 ml of red blood cells. MCHC is a useful parameter in evaluating the hemoglobin content and density of red blood cells.\r\n\r\nTo calculate MCHC, the hemoglobin content is divided by the hematocrit and multiplied by 100. The hematocrit represents the volume of packed red blood cells in relation to the total blood volume. Therefore, MCHC provides information about the hemoglobin concentration within the red blood cells.\r\n\r\nMCHC values are typically expressed in grams per deciliter (g/dL) or grams per liter (g/L). Normal MCHC values range between 32-36 g/dL.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that MCHC is just one of the parameters used to assess the characteristics of red blood cells. Other parameters, such as Mean Corpuscular Volume (MCV) and Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin (MCH), are also used in the evaluation of red blood cell indices.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 635.\r\n\r\n(2) Sarma PR, Walker HK, Hall WD, Hurst JW. Red cell indices. Clinical Methods: The History, Physical, and Laboratory Examinations. Published 1990. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK260/\r\n(3) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Mean corpuscular volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin index","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hematocrit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mean corpuscular hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12541,"text":"A person with blood group AB+ve can safely donate blood in an emergency to a patient with which of the following blood groups?","explanation":"Blood compatibility is determined by the presence or absence of certain antigens on the surface of red blood cells. The ABO blood group system consists of four main blood types: A, B, AB, and O. Additionally, blood is classified as either Rh-positive (Rh+) or Rh-negative (Rh-), based on the presence or absence of the Rh antigen.\r\n\r\nA person with blood group AB has both A and B antigens on their red blood cells, while individuals with blood group O lack both A and B antigens. The \"+\" or \"-\" symbol indicates the presence or absence of the Rh antigen, respectively.\r\n\r\nIn emergency situations, individuals with AB+ve blood are considered universal donors for other AB+ve individuals. This is because individuals with AB+ve blood have both A and B antigens on their red blood cells, making them compatible with all other blood groups that do not have antibodies against A or B antigens.\r\n\r\nHowever, it's important to note that in non-emergency situations, blood transfusions are ideally matched according to the ABO and Rh systems to minimize the risk of transfusion reactions.","reference":"AB positive blood type. NHS Blood Donation. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.blood.co.uk/why-give-blood/blood-types/ab-positive-blood-type/","responses":[{"text":"B+ve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"O+ve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"AB+ve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"AB-ve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A+ve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12542,"text":"In which of the following organs is the heme mainly converted to bilirubin?","explanation":"The breakdown of heme, the pigment found in hemoglobin, leads to the production of bilirubin. This process primarily occurs in the reticuloendothelial system, with the spleen being the major site of heme catabolism.\r\n\r\nIn the reticuloendothelial cells of the spleen, macrophages phagocytize aged and damaged red blood cells. These macrophages break down heme into biliverdin, which is subsequently converted to unconjugated bilirubin. Unconjugated bilirubin is then released into the bloodstream and bound to albumin for transport to the liver.\r\n\r\nIn the liver, unconjugated bilirubin is taken up by hepatocytes, where it is conjugated with glucuronic acid to form water-soluble bilirubin glucuronides. These conjugated bilirubin glucuronides are excreted into the bile and ultimately eliminated from the body via the feces.\r\n\r\nWhile heme breakdown also occurs in other tissues, such as the bone marrow and liver, the spleen plays a crucial role in the initial step of heme conversion to bilirubin.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Kidney","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12543,"text":"When a serum sample is electrophoresed, which of the following band is normally absent?","explanation":"Serum protein electrophoresis is a laboratory test used to separate and quantify the different proteins present in the serum based on their electrophoretic mobility. The proteins are separated into distinct bands on the electrophoresis gel.\r\n\r\nThe major bands seen in serum protein electrophoresis are albumin, alpha-1 globulin, alpha-2 globulin, beta globulin, and gamma globulin. Fibrinogen, which is a clotting protein, is normally absent in serum because it is consumed during the clotting process and does not circulate in its active form. Fibrinogen is converted to fibrin during blood clot formation, and thus it is not present in the serum sample used for electrophoresis.\r\n\r\nThe absence of a fibrinogen band is an expected finding in serum protein electrophoresis, as fibrinogen is not a major component of circulating serum proteins. The presence of a fibrinogen band in serum electrophoresis could indicate abnormal clotting or contamination of the serum sample with plasma.","reference":"Tripathy S. The role of serum protein electrophoresis in the detection of multiple myeloma: an experience of a corporate hospital. Journal of Clinical and Diagnostic Research : JCDR. Published November 2012. Accessed November 21, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3527769/","responses":[{"text":"Alpha-2 globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alpha-1 globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gamma globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12544,"text":"A patient has been diagnosed with Hepatitis type A virus. which type of immunity will they develop in response to the above-mentioned disease?","explanation":"Hepatitis A virus (HAV) infection leads to the development of natural active immunity. Natural active immunity is acquired when a person's immune system is exposed to an infectious agent, such as a virus or bacterium, and mounts an immune response to eliminate the pathogen. In the case of HAV infection, the immune system recognizes the virus as foreign and activates various components of the immune response to clear the infection.\r\n\r\nDuring an HAV infection, the immune system produces antibodies, specifically IgM and IgG antibodies, which target and neutralize the virus. IgM antibodies are the first to appear during the acute phase of the infection, while IgG antibodies develop later and provide long-term immunity against future HAV exposures.\r\n\r\nThis acquired immunity helps protect the individual from subsequent HAV infections by providing a rapid and efficient immune response, preventing reinfection or reducing the severity of symptoms.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 469.","responses":[{"text":"Innate immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural active immunity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Artificial active immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Artificial passive immunity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural passive immunity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12545,"text":"A 55-year-old man presents to the emergency room with a complaint of sudden pain in his chest. Based on his electrocardiogram(ECG) and the presence of cardiac enzymes in the blood sample, a diagnosis of myocardial infarction is made. He is given a fibrinolytic agent to dissolve the clot in his coronary blood vessel. Which of the following substance was most likely activated by this agent to dissolve the clot?","explanation":"In the scenario described, the patient with a myocardial infarction is given a fibrinolytic agent to dissolve the clot in his coronary blood vessel. Fibrinolytic agents such as tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) or streptokinase work by converting plasminogen to plasmin.\r\n\r\n**Plasminogen** is an inactive precursor molecule present in the blood. Upon activation by fibrinolytic agents, plasminogen is converted to its active form, **plasmin**. Plasmin functions as a proteolytic enzyme that degrades fibrin, the major component of blood clots. By breaking down fibrin, plasmin helps to dissolve the clot and restore blood flow in the occluded coronary vessel.\r\n\r\nOther options mentioned in the question stem, such as clotting factor XII, bradykinin, prothrombin, and fibrinogen, are not directly involved in the fibrinolytic process. Factor XII is part of the intrinsic pathway of coagulation, bradykinin is involved in vasodilation and inflammation, prothrombin is a precursor of thrombin, and fibrinogen is converted to fibrin during clot formation.","reference":"Baig MU, Bodle J. Thrombolytic therapy. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed November 21, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557411/","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bradykinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clotting factor XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasminogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12546,"text":"Which of the following factors is immediately released from the injured vascular endothelium to cause vasoconstriction?","explanation":"When vascular endothelium is injured, it releases various factors that regulate vascular tone and function. One of these factors is **endothelin**. Endothelin is a potent vasoconstrictor peptide that is synthesized and released by endothelial cells in response to injury or inflammation.\r\n\r\nEndothelin acts on smooth muscle cells in blood vessels, leading to vasoconstriction and a decrease in blood flow. It exerts its effects by binding to endothelin receptors on smooth muscle cells, triggering intracellular signaling pathways that result in smooth muscle contraction.\r\n\r\nThis vasoconstrictive effect of endothelin helps to minimize bleeding and prevent excessive blood loss following injury. It also contributes to the regulation of blood pressure and vascular tone under normal physiological conditions.\r\n\r\nOther options mentioned in the question stem, such as thromboxane A2, bradykinin, serotonin, and vasopressin, are also involved in vascular regulation but have different roles and mechanisms of action compared to endothelin.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 210.","responses":[{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endothelin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serotonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bradykinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasopressin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12555,"text":"The first step of heme synthesis takes place in which part of the cell?","explanation":"The first step of heme synthesis occurs in the mitochondria. Heme synthesis is a complex pathway that involves multiple enzymes and intermediates. The synthesis begins with the formation of **delta-aminolevulinic acid (ALA)**, which is the initial precursor of heme. This step is catalyzed by the enzyme **delta-aminolevulinic acid synthase (ALAS)**.\r\n\r\nALAS is located in the mitochondria and converts **glycine** and **succinyl-CoA** into ALA. The reaction occurs in the mitochondrial matrix. ALA then undergoes a series of enzymatic steps both in the mitochondria and cytoplasm to form heme.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that the subsequent steps of heme synthesis occur in the cytoplasm and involve different enzymes and intermediates. The final product, heme, is then incorporated into various heme-containing proteins, such as hemoglobin, myoglobin, and cytochromes.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Mitochondria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Peroxisome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Golgi apparatus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12556,"text":"In which of the following stages of erythropoiesis, does hemoglobin make its appearance?","explanation":"During erythropoiesis, the process of red blood cell formation, the appearance of hemoglobin coincides with the stage of **polychromatophil erythroblast**. Polychromatophil erythroblasts are nucleated precursor cells that contain a high concentration of ribosomes and are actively synthesizing hemoglobin. These cells have a bluish-gray cytoplasm due to the presence of both basophilic and eosinophilic components.\r\n\r\nIn earlier stages of erythropoiesis, such as the **proerythroblast** and **basophil erythroblast** stages, the cells are actively dividing and increasing in size but have not yet started synthesizing hemoglobin. Once the cells progress to the polychromatophil erythroblast stage, they begin to accumulate hemoglobin in their cytoplasm.\r\n\r\nAs the cells mature further, they become **orthochromatic erythroblasts**, where the nucleus becomes more condensed, and the cell begins to lose its organelles. Finally, in the last stage of erythropoiesis, the **reticulocyte** stage, the nucleus is ejected, and the cell becomes a mature red blood cell.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Orthochromatic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colony forming unit-erythrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophil erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proerythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polychromatophil erythroblast","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12557,"text":"Which of the following substances promotes platelet plug formation?","explanation":"Thromboxane A2 is a potent platelet activator and promotes platelet plug formation. Platelet plug formation is a crucial step in hemostasis, the process of stopping bleeding. When blood vessel injury occurs, platelets become activated and adhere to the site of injury to form a platelet plug, which helps to seal the damaged blood vessel. Thromboxane A2 is released by activated platelets and acts as a vasoconstrictor, enhances platelet aggregation, and promotes the recruitment of additional platelets to the site of injury.\r\n\r\nAmong the given options, **prostacyclin** (PGI2) has an opposite function to thromboxane A2. Prostacyclin is synthesized by the endothelium and acts as a potent inhibitor of platelet aggregation and a vasodilator.\r\n\r\nOther options such as **aspirin** inhibit platelet aggregation by irreversibly inhibiting the enzyme cyclooxygenase (COX), which is involved in the production of thromboxane A2. **ADP dephosphatase** is not directly involved in platelet plug formation, and **nitric oxide** primarily functions as a vasodilator and inhibits platelet aggregation.\r\n\r\nOverall, thromboxane A2 plays a critical role in promoting platelet plug formation during hemostasis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Prostacyclin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ADP dephosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric oxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12559,"text":"Which of the following growth inducers promotes the growth and reproduction of all types of committed stem cells?","explanation":"Interleukin-3 (IL-3) is a cytokine that plays a crucial role in hematopoiesis, the process of forming blood cells. It acts as a growth inducer for various types of committed stem cells, including erythroid, myeloid, and lymphoid progenitor cells.\r\n\r\nIL-3 stimulates the proliferation and differentiation of these stem cells, promoting the production of red blood cells, granulocytes, monocytes, platelets, and lymphocytes. By supporting the growth and reproduction of different cell lineages, IL-3 plays a vital role in maintaining a functional and balanced hematopoietic system.\r\n\r\nWhile other interleukins, such as Interleukin-2, Interleukin-1, Interleukin-5, and Interleukin-4, have important roles in immune responses and specific cell types, IL-3 is unique in its ability to stimulate the growth and reproduction of various committed stem cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Interleukin-2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-4","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12560,"text":"Which of the following clotting factors initiates the extrinsic pathway of the clotting cascade?","explanation":"The clotting cascade consists of intrinsic and extrinsic pathways that eventually converge to activate the common pathway and form a blood clot. The extrinsic pathway is initiated by the activation of Factor III, also known as Tissue Factor (TF).\r\n\r\nTissue Factor is released from damaged tissues, such as in the case of injury or trauma. Once released, it forms a complex with Factor VII, known as the tissue factor-Factor VIIa complex. This complex activates Factor X to Factor Xa, which subsequently leads to the conversion of prothrombin (Factor II) to thrombin (Factor IIa) in the common pathway.\r\n\r\nThe extrinsic pathway provides a rapid and localized response to tissue damage and is essential for initiating clot formation. In contrast, the intrinsic pathway is activated by contact with exposed collagen and other negatively charged surfaces.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that clotting factors are often referred to by their Roman numerals, with Factor III corresponding to Tissue Factor.","reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.\r\n(2) Barmore W, Bajwa T, Burns B. Biochemistry, clotting factors. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 11, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507850/","responses":[{"text":"V","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"II","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"III","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12561,"text":"The common pathway in the clotting mechanism is the activation of which of the following factors?","explanation":"The clotting mechanism involves a series of reactions known as the coagulation cascade, which can be divided into intrinsic and extrinsic pathways. These pathways eventually converge into a common pathway, leading to the activation of factor X.\r\n\r\nFactor X, also known as Stuart-Prower factor, is a key component of the coagulation cascade. It is activated by both the intrinsic and extrinsic pathways. In the intrinsic pathway, factor X is activated by the enzymatic complex known as the tenase complex, which consists of activated factor IX (IXa), activated factor VIII (VIIIa), calcium ions, and platelet phospholipids. In the extrinsic pathway, factor X is activated by tissue factor (TF) released from damaged tissues, along with activated factor VII (VIIa), calcium ions, and tissue factor pathway inhibitor (TFPI).\r\n\r\nOnce activated, factor X converts prothrombin (factor II) into thrombin (factor IIa) in the final common pathway. Thrombin then plays a central role in the conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin, leading to the formation of a stable blood clot.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"XIII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"XI","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12562,"text":"Which of the following ions is essential for the coagulation of blood?","explanation":"Calcium plays a critical role in the coagulation cascade, which is the series of reactions that leads to the formation of a blood clot. In the absence of calcium, the coagulation process cannot occur effectively.\r\n\r\nCalcium ions are required at several steps of the coagulation pathway. One of the key steps is the activation of coagulation factors, particularly factors IX, X, and II (prothrombin). Calcium ions act as a cofactor for the enzymatic reactions that convert these inactive factors into their active forms. Additionally, calcium is involved in the formation of the fibrin clot, where it helps stabilize the fibrin network and promotes the cross-linking of fibrin strands.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that the concentration of calcium in the blood must be tightly regulated for proper coagulation. Low levels of calcium can impair clot formation, while excessively high levels can lead to abnormal clotting and increased risk of thrombosis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pottasium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloride","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12563,"text":"Which of the following factors catalyzes the conversion of fibrinogen into fibrin?","explanation":"Thrombin is a key enzyme in the coagulation cascade that plays a crucial role in blood clotting. It is produced through the activation of prothrombin by thromboplastin, which is released following tissue injury. Thrombin acts on fibrinogen, a soluble plasma protein, and catalyzes its conversion into fibrin, an insoluble protein that forms the meshwork of a blood clot.\r\n\r\nThe conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin occurs through the proteolytic cleavage of specific peptide bonds by thrombin. Thrombin cleaves two small peptides, fibrinopeptide A and fibrinopeptide B, from the fibrinogen molecule, exposing specific binding sites that allow the fibrin monomers to polymerize. Polymerization of the fibrin monomers leads to the formation of a fibrin clot, which stabilizes the platelet plug and prevents further bleeding.\r\n\r\nThrombin also plays additional roles in the coagulation process, including the activation of platelets, amplification of coagulation factors, and feedback regulation of its own formation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 479.","responses":[{"text":"Plasminogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboplastin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prothrombin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12564,"text":"The von Willebrand factor plays an important role in which of the following processes of hemostasis?","explanation":"The von Willebrand factor (vWF) plays a crucial role in the process of hemostasis by facilitating platelet adhesion. During vessel injury, the vWF is released from endothelial cells and platelets. It acts as a bridge between platelets and the exposed subendothelial matrix or damaged vessel wall. The vWF binds to platelet surface receptors, particularly the glycoprotein Ib (GPIb) receptor, and to the exposed collagen fibers of the vessel wall.\r\n\r\nPlatelet adhesion is the initial step in hemostasis, where platelets adhere to the damaged vessel wall to form a platelet plug. The vWF promotes platelet adhesion by binding to the platelet surface and anchoring it to the site of injury. This allows platelets to aggregate and form a plug, preventing further bleeding.\r\n\r\nOther options mentioned in the question stem, such as platelet aggregation, activation of thrombin, clot dissolution, and clot formation, involve different stages of hemostasis but are not primarily mediated by the von Willebrand factor.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Activation of thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clot dissolution","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet aggregation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet adhesion","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clot formation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12565,"text":"A patient with prolonged prothrombin time(PT) and normal activated partial prothrombin time(APTT) indicates which of the following conditions?","explanation":"A patient with prolonged prothrombin time (PT) and normal activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT) suggests **factor VII deficiency**.\r\n\r\nProthrombin time (PT) measures the extrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade, which is primarily dependent on factors VII, X, V, II, and fibrinogen. A prolonged PT indicates a deficiency or dysfunction of one or more of these factors. In this case, the PT is prolonged while the APTT, which measures the intrinsic pathway, is normal. This suggests an isolated deficiency of factor VII.\r\n\r\nFactor VII is a vitamin K-dependent clotting factor that plays a crucial role in initiating the extrinsic pathway of coagulation. It is synthesized in the liver and is activated upon tissue injury. Deficiency or dysfunction of factor VII impairs the initiation of the clotting cascade, leading to a prolonged PT.\r\n\r\nOther options, such as platelet dysfunction or deficiencies of factors II, IV, or VIII, would affect both the PT and APTT, resulting in prolonged APTT as well.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 662.","responses":[{"text":"Factor IV deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor II deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII deficiency","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12568,"text":"Which clotting factor is activated first in the intrinsic pathway of blood clotting?","explanation":"Factor XII is the clotting factor that is activated first in the intrinsic pathway of blood clotting.\r\n\r\nThe intrinsic pathway is initiated by factor XII, also known as Hageman factor. Upon contact with exposed collagen or negatively charged surfaces, factor XII undergoes autoactivation, converting it into its active form, factor XIIa. Factor XIIa then catalyzes the activation of factor XI, leading to a cascade of enzymatic reactions that ultimately results in the formation of a fibrin clot.\r\n\r\nFactor XII activation occurs independently of tissue injury and is triggered by factors such as contact with foreign surfaces, platelets, or activated endothelial cells. It serves as a bridge between the initial injury and the activation of other clotting factors in the intrinsic pathway.\r\n\r\nThe other factors listed (IX, VIII, III, VII) are involved in different stages of the clotting cascade but are not the initial activators in the intrinsic pathway.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 482.","responses":[{"text":"Factor IX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12569,"text":"Which of the following molecules is a primary factor in the margination of neutrophils?","explanation":"Tumor necrosis factor (TNF) is a primary factor in the margination of neutrophils.\r\n\r\nMargination refers to the process by which neutrophils move from the central bloodstream to the periphery of blood vessels, where they can effectively migrate to sites of inflammation or infection. TNF is a pro-inflammatory cytokine released by activated macrophages and other immune cells in response to infection or tissue injury.\r\n\r\nTNF induces the expression of adhesion molecules on the endothelial cells lining the blood vessels, such as selectins and integrins. These adhesion molecules facilitate the tethering and rolling of neutrophils along the vessel wall, allowing them to adhere and migrate into the surrounding tissues.\r\n\r\nWhile other molecules such as interleukin-8 (IL-8) also play a role in neutrophil recruitment and activation, TNF is particularly important in the initial margination process by promoting the expression of adhesion molecules on the endothelium.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 454, 455.","responses":[{"text":"Selectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tumor necrosis factor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Integrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adherin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12570,"text":"In which of the following stages of erythropoiesis, the cell has a condensed nucleus, 34 percent hemoglobin, and reabsorbed endoplasmic reticulum?","explanation":"During erythropoiesis, reticulocytes are the final stage of maturation before the development of mature erythrocytes. Reticulocytes still contain some organelles, including ribosomes and remnants of the endoplasmic reticulum. These organelles contribute to the synthesis of hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nReticulocytes can be identified by their characteristic appearance under a microscope, where they exhibit a mesh-like or reticular pattern due to the residual ribosomes. The percentage of reticulocytes in the blood is an indicator of erythropoietic activity.\r\n\r\nAt this stage, reticulocytes have a condensed nucleus, as the nucleus undergoes extrusion during maturation. They contain approximately 34 percent hemoglobin, which is gradually increasing as they mature into fully functional erythrocytes. Reticulocytes are released into the bloodstream, where they further mature into erythrocytes and acquire their characteristic biconcave shape.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Orthochromatic erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophil erythrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polychromatophil erythroblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reticulocyte","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12571,"text":"Which of the following is the most potent antigen-presenting cell, among the major types of antigen-presenting cells?","explanation":"Dendritic cells are the most potent antigen-presenting cells (APCs) among the major types.\r\n\r\nDendritic cells (DCs) are specialized immune cells that play a crucial role in initiating and regulating immune responses. They are found in tissues throughout the body, especially in the skin, mucosal surfaces, and lymphoid organs. DCs have a unique ability to capture antigens, process them, and present them to T cells, thereby activating an adaptive immune response.\r\n\r\nDendritic cells are considered the most potent APCs due to their exceptional antigen-presenting capabilities. They possess a high density of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class II molecules on their surface, which are responsible for presenting antigens to helper T cells. Additionally, dendritic cells express co-stimulatory molecules that facilitate T cell activation.\r\n\r\nThe potent antigen-presenting function of dendritic cells allows them to efficiently prime naïve T cells and initiate adaptive immune responses against specific antigens.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 466.","responses":[{"text":"Macrophages","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"B lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helper-T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxic-T cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dendritic cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12619,"text":"Which of the following changes shifts the oxygen dissociation curve to the left?","explanation":"An increase in pH (alkalosis) shifts the oxygen dissociation curve to the left.\r\n\r\nThe oxygen dissociation curve represents the relationship between the partial pressure of oxygen (PO2) and the saturation of hemoglobin with oxygen. A leftward shift of the curve indicates an increased affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen, meaning that hemoglobin is more readily bound to oxygen at a given PO2.\r\n\r\nAn increase in pH, or a decrease in hydrogen ion concentration (alkalosis), causes the oxygen dissociation curve to shift to the left. This shift occurs because alkalosis promotes a more alkaline environment, which favors the binding of oxygen to hemoglobin. In alkalosis, there is a reduction in the release of hydrogen ions (H+) from hemoglobin, leading to a higher affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen.\r\n\r\nThe leftward shift of the oxygen dissociation curve in alkalosis ensures that oxygen is more readily bound to hemoglobin in the lungs, facilitating its uptake and transport to the tissues.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 30.","responses":[{"text":"Rise in 2,3-diphosphoglyerate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rise in hydrogen ion concentration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rise in pH","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rise in carbon di oxide tension","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rise in temperature","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12620,"text":"Which of the following enzymes in the heme biosynthesis pathway requires pyridoxal phosphate as a coenzyme?","explanation":"Aminolevulinic acid synthase is the enzyme in the heme biosynthesis pathway that requires pyridoxal phosphate as a coenzyme.\r\n\r\nAminolevulinic acid synthase is responsible for the condensation of glycine and succinyl-CoA to form aminolevulinic acid (ALA), which is the first committed step in the heme biosynthesis pathway. This enzyme requires the presence of pyridoxal phosphate, the active form of vitamin B6, as a coenzyme to catalyze the reaction.\r\n\r\nPyridoxal phosphate serves as a cofactor for many enzymatic reactions, including those involved in amino acid metabolism. It acts as a carrier of functional groups and plays a crucial role in the conversion of substrates in various metabolic pathways.\r\n\r\nIn the heme biosynthesis pathway, the presence of pyridoxal phosphate allows aminolevulinic acid synthase to carry out the condensation reaction, leading to the formation of ALA. This step is essential for the subsequent synthesis of heme, which is required for the production of hemoglobin and other heme-containing proteins.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Ferrochelatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coproporphyrinogen deaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Porphobilinogen deaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminolevulinic acid dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminolevulinic acid synthase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12621,"text":"A 7-year-old boy developed vesicles and bullae on his face and arms due to prolonged sun exposure from participating in sports activities. His father had a similar condition. He is suspected of porphyria cutanea tarda. Which of the following enzymes is mainly deficient in the above-mentioned disease condition?","explanation":"In porphyria cutanea tarda (PCT), the main enzyme deficiency is **uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase**.\r\n\r\nUroporphyrinogen decarboxylase is an enzyme involved in the heme biosynthesis pathway. It catalyzes the conversion of uroporphyrinogen III to coproporphyrinogen III, which is a crucial step in the synthesis of heme. Heme is an essential component of hemoglobin and other heme-containing proteins.\r\n\r\nIn individuals with PCT, there is a deficiency of uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase, leading to the accumulation of uroporphyrinogen III and its derivatives in the liver and other tissues. This accumulation is triggered by factors such as exposure to sunlight, alcohol consumption, and certain medications.\r\n\r\nThe excess uroporphyrinogen III and its derivatives are photosensitive and can be activated by sunlight, resulting in the formation of reactive oxygen species and damage to the skin. This manifests as vesicles, bullae, and skin fragility, particularly in sun-exposed areas.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 280.","responses":[{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen deaminase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen dehydratase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12623,"text":"The corrin ring in cobalamin(vitamin B12), is bound to which of the following trace elements?","explanation":"The corrin ring in cobalamin (vitamin B12) is bound to the trace element **cobalt**.\r\n\r\nCobalamin, also known as vitamin B12, is a complex molecule that plays a crucial role in various physiological processes, including DNA synthesis, red blood cell production, and neurological function. The corrin ring is a unique structure in cobalamin that contains a central cobalt atom.\r\n\r\nCobalt is an essential trace element that is required for the synthesis of cobalamin. It forms a stable coordination complex with the corrin ring, giving cobalamin its distinctive structure. The cobalt atom is located at the center of the corrin ring and is directly involved in the binding and transport of certain molecules, such as methyl groups, in various enzymatic reactions.\r\n\r\nThe binding of cobalt to the corrin ring is essential for the biological activity of cobalamin and its role as a coenzyme in numerous biochemical pathways.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 375.","responses":[{"text":"Cobalt","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selenium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zinc","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12626,"text":"Iron is transported to the bone marrow by which of the following proteins?","explanation":"**Iron** is transported to the bone marrow by **transferrin**. Transferrin is a glycoprotein produced by the liver that binds to iron and transports it in the bloodstream. It is responsible for carrying iron from sites of absorption or storage to cells that require iron, such as the bone marrow for red blood cell production. Transferrin binds to iron through its specific binding sites and delivers it to cells by interacting with transferrin receptors on cell surfaces. Once inside the cells, iron is released from transferrin and utilized for various metabolic processes, including hemoglobin synthesis.","reference":"Knutson MD. Iron transport proteins: Gateways of cellular and systemic iron homeostasis. The Journal of Biological Chemistry. Published August 4, 2017. Accessed November 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5546014/","responses":[{"text":"Transferrin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C-reactive protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apoferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemosiderin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12627,"text":"Which of the following are the regions in immunoglobulins that contain three-dimensional antigen binding sites complementary to the structure of the specific antigen?","explanation":"The **variable regions** of immunoglobulins (antibodies) contain the **three-dimensional antigen binding sites** that are complementary to the structure of specific antigens. These variable regions are located at the **N-terminal ends** of both the **heavy and light chains of the antibody**. The variable regions consist of hypervariable loops, also known as complementarity-determining regions (CDRs), which directly interact with the antigen.\r\n\r\nThe constant regions, on the other hand, determine the effector functions and class/subclass of the antibody molecule. They are responsible for interactions with other immune cells and molecules involved in immune responses.\r\n\r\nThe crystallizable region (Fc region) is located at the C-terminal end of the heavy chain and is responsible for antibody effector functions such as binding to Fc receptors on immune cells and triggering immune responses.\r\n\r\nThe hinge region is a flexible region that connects the two Fab arms to the Fc region and allows for flexibility and movement of the antibody molecule.\r\n\r\nDi-sulfide regions refer to the regions of the antibody where disulfide bonds are formed between cysteine residues, contributing to the structural stability of the antibody molecule.","reference":"Schroeder HW, Cavacini L. Structure and function of immunoglobulins. The Journal of allergy and clinical immunology. Published February 2010. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3670108/","responses":[{"text":"Crystallizable regions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variable regions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Di-sulphide regions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constant regions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hinge regions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12628,"text":"Which of the following is the region in the primary structure of immunoglobulins that determines the antibody class?","explanation":"The primary structure of immunoglobulins, also known as antibodies, consists of two types of chains: **heavy chains** and **light chains**. Each chain has a **variable region** and a **constant region**. The variable regions of both heavy and light chains contribute to the **antigen-binding site** of the antibody, providing specificity for **antigen recognition**.\r\n\r\nHowever, it is the constant region of the heavy chain that determines the **antibody class or isotype**. The constant region of the heavy chain determines the effector functions and other characteristics of the antibody, such as its ability to activate complement, cross the placenta, or bind to specific cell receptors. There are five main antibody classes or isotypes: IgM, IgG, IgA, IgD, and IgE, and each class has a distinct constant region of the heavy chain.","reference":"Charles A Janeway J, Travers P, Walport M, Shlomchik MJ. The structure of a typical antibody molecule. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. Published 2001. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK27144/","responses":[{"text":"Constant region of heavy chain","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Variable region of light chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Variable region of heavy chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypervariable region of light chain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Constant region of light chain","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12629,"text":"An increase in total protein with normal levels of albumin and increased globulin is due to which of the following conditions?","explanation":"An increase in **total protein** with **normal levels of albumin** and **increased globulin** is commonly seen in **multiple myeloma**.\r\n\r\nMultiple myeloma is a type of cancer that affects plasma cells, which are a type of white blood cell responsible for producing antibodies. In multiple myeloma, abnormal plasma cells multiply uncontrollably, leading to the production of large amounts of abnormal immunoglobulins (antibodies) called monoclonal proteins or M proteins. These M proteins contribute to the increased globulin fraction in the total protein measurement.\r\n\r\nIn this condition, the levels of albumin, which is the most abundant protein in the blood, may remain within the normal range or may be slightly decreased. However, the overall increase in total protein is predominantly due to the elevated globulin levels, specifically the M proteins produced by the malignant plasma cells.\r\n\r\nIt's worth noting that an increase in total protein with normal levels of albumin and increased globulin can also be observed in other conditions, such as chronic inflammation, certain infections, and autoimmune diseases. However, in the given options, multiple myeloma is the most likely cause.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 611.\r\n(2) Albagoush SA, Shumway C, Azevedo AM. Multiple myeloma. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534764/","responses":[{"text":"Multiple myeloma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malabsorption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inadequate diet","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Burns and trauma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12630,"text":"C-reactive protein, which is elevated in case of inflammation and infection, falls into the category of which of the following plasma proteins?","explanation":"**C-reactive protein (CRP)** falls into the category of **acute phase proteins**.\r\n\r\nAcute phase proteins are a group of proteins that are produced by the liver in response to inflammation, infection, or tissue injury. They are part of the innate immune response and play a role in the early stages of the body's defense mechanisms. CRP is one of the major acute phase proteins and its levels increase rapidly in response to inflammation or infection. Elevated levels of CRP can be seen in various conditions, including bacterial and viral infections, tissue injury, autoimmune diseases, and certain cancers. CRP levels can be measured through a blood test and are used as a marker of inflammation in clinical practice.","reference":"Sproston NR, Ashworth JJ. Role of c-reactive protein at sites of inflammation and infection. Frontiers in Immunology. Published April 13, 2018. Accessed November 23, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5908901/","responses":[{"text":"Oncotic proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute phase proteins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transport proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma enzymes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clotting proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12631,"text":"In red blood cells, when 2,3-biphosphoglycerate combines with hemoglobin in high concentrations, it causes which of the following changes?","explanation":"When **2,3-biphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG)** combines with hemoglobin in high concentrations, it causes a shift of the **oxygen dissociation curve** to the **right**.\r\n\r\nThe oxygen dissociation curve represents the relationship between the **partial pressure of oxygen (PO2)** and the **percentage of hemoglobin saturated with oxygen (oxygen saturation)**. When 2,3-BPG binds to hemoglobin, it decreases the affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen, facilitating the release of oxygen to tissues. This shift to the right means that at any given partial pressure of oxygen, hemoglobin has a lower affinity for oxygen and is more readily released to the tissues.\r\n\r\nThis shift is important in tissues with high metabolic demands, such as exercising muscles or tissues at high altitudes. The presence of 2,3-BPG helps ensure efficient oxygen delivery to these tissues by promoting oxygen release from hemoglobin.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 31.","responses":[{"text":"No change in oxy-hemoglobin dissociation curve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Displacement of the oxy-hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift of oxygen dissociation curve to the left","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shift of oxygen dissociation curve to the right","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12784,"text":"A 5-year-old boy is brought to the emergency room with a history of a knee injury. On physical examination, the knee is found to be painful and swollen. The boy's mother told the physician that one of his maternal uncles died from a bleeding disorder. What is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"**Hemophilia A** is a hereditary bleeding disorder caused by a deficiency or dysfunction of **clotting factor VIII**. It is an X-linked recessive disorder, which means it primarily affects males and is usually inherited from carrier mothers. In this case, the **maternal uncle's** history of a bleeding disorder suggests a possibility of **X-linked inheritance**.\r\n\r\nThe presentation of a painful and swollen knee following a knee injury is consistent with hemarthrosis, which is a common manifestation of hemophilia. Hemophilia is characterized by a tendency to bleed excessively and for a longer duration after injuries or surgeries.\r\n\r\nPlatelet function defects and von Willebrand disease can also present with bleeding symptoms, but the history of a maternal uncle with a bleeding disorder makes hemophilia A more likely. Hemophilia B is also X-linked but is less common than hemophilia A.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 668.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet function defect","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12785,"text":"A 4-year-old boy is brought to the outpatient clinic with complaints of frequent nosebleeds and an episode of blood in his stools two months ago. His parents and his elder sister were all healthy. His mother informed the doctor, that one of her brothers was also suffering from the same symptoms. The doctor advised laboratory investigations to evaluate his coagulation profile. The disease he is suffering from has which one of the following etiologies?","explanation":"The presence of frequent nosebleeds and blood in stools, along with a family history of the same symptoms in the boy's uncle, suggests a **bleeding disorder**. Inherited bleeding disorders can be caused by various genetic mechanisms. One of the common genetic patterns for bleeding disorders is X-linked inheritance.\r\n\r\n**X-linked inheritance** refers to the inheritance of a genetic condition caused by a mutation in a gene located on the X chromosome. In this pattern, the gene mutation is typically passed from carrier mothers to their affected sons. Carrier females may not exhibit symptoms themselves but can pass the gene mutation to their male offspring.\r\n\r\nThe fact that the boy's mother is healthy and her brother has similar symptoms suggests that the disease may be X-linked recessive. In X-linked recessive disorders, **affected males** usually inherit the mutation from their carrier mothers, while **carrier females** have a 50% chance of passing the mutation to their male offspring.\r\n\r\nFurther laboratory investigations are necessary to confirm the diagnosis and identify the specific bleeding disorder involved.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multigenic disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12786,"text":"A patient was diagnosed with megaloblastic anemia. Why should she be treated with both folic acid and vitamin B12?","explanation":"**Megaloblastic anemia** is characterized by the impaired production of red blood cells due to deficiencies in either **folic acid (vitamin B9)** or **vitamin B12**. Both folic acid and vitamin B12 are essential for **DNA synthesis** and **red blood cell formation**.\r\n\r\nFolic acid is necessary for the synthesis of purine and pyrimidine bases, which are building blocks of DNA. However, folic acid needs to be converted to its active form, tetrahydrofolate (THF), in order to participate in these processes. This conversion of folic acid to THF requires the presence of vitamin B12 as a cofactor.\r\n\r\nWhen a patient with megaloblastic anemia is treated with folic acid alone, it can lead to the improvement of hematologic symptoms, such as the production of normal-sized red blood cells. However, folic acid supplementation alone does not address the underlying vitamin B12 deficiency, which can cause neurological damage.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 deficiency can lead to neurological complications, including peripheral neuropathy and spinal cord degeneration. If folic acid is administered without addressing the vitamin B12 deficiency, it can improve hematologic symptoms but worsen neurologic symptoms. This is because folic acid supplementation can correct the anemia but not the underlying vitamin B12 deficiency responsible for the neurological damage.\r\n\r\nTherefore, it is crucial to treat megaloblastic anemia with both **folic acid** and **vitamin B12**. Folic acid supplementation improves hematologic symptoms, while vitamin B12 supplementation addresses the underlying deficiency and prevents potential worsening of neurologic symptoms.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 653.","responses":[{"text":"Folic acid alone causes improvement of hematologic symptoms but can cause worsening of neurologic symptoms","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid does not work alone unless supplemented with vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid alone can cause worsening of both hematologic and neurologic symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12 decreases folic acid toxicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid requires vitamin B12 for activation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13003,"text":"A 55-year-old man was diagnosed with constrictive pericarditis, two years after suffering from trauma to the heart. When he died an autopsy was performed. The heart was encased in a thickened, fibrotic pericardium. The pericardium was attached to the heart by a stingy material that was difficult to remove. What type of inflammation did the patient have in his pericardium?","explanation":"**Fibrinous inflammation** is characterized by the exudation of **fibrin-rich fluid** into the affected tissue or body cavity. It typically occurs in response to severe injury or inflammation and is associated with increased vascular permeability and the leakage of fibrinogen into the affected area. The fibrinogen is then converted into fibrin, forming a meshwork that can adhere to the tissue surfaces and create adhesions.\r\n\r\nIn the case of the patient with **constrictive pericarditis**, the thickened and fibrotic pericardium that encased the heart suggests the presence of chronic inflammation. The formation of adhesions between the pericardium and the heart indicates the involvement of fibrinous inflammation.","reference":"Bhatti R, Sonani B, Dhamoon AS. Fibrinous pericarditis. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 6, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538254/","responses":[{"text":"Serous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ulcerative","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrinous","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Purulent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Catarrhal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13005,"text":"Which of the following mediators of inflammation cause symptoms of headache, fever, and pain in the sinuses in individuals sick with flu?","explanation":"**Prostaglandins** are lipid mediators of inflammation that are produced during the **inflammatory response**, including in cases of **viral infections** such as the flu. They contribute to the development of **fever, headache**, and **pain in the sinuses**. Prostaglandins are synthesized from arachidonic acid through the action of the enzyme cyclooxygenase (COX). Inhibition of COX by nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) can help reduce these symptoms. Histamine, chemokines, leukotrienes, and kinins can also contribute to the inflammatory response, but they are not specifically associated with the symptoms described in individuals with flu.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 85.","responses":[{"text":"Kinins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotrienes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemokines","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13007,"text":"A 65-year-old woman is being treated for pain and inflammation in her joints for the past year. Which of the following statements regarding the patient's inflammation is correct?","explanation":"**Chronic inflammation**, as described in the scenario, is characterized by the simultaneous presence of inflammation, tissue destruction, and attempts at tissue repair. Unlike acute inflammation, which is typically characterized by a neutrophilic infiltrate, chronic inflammation involves the **infiltration of mononuclear cells such as lymphocytes and macrophages**. Abscess formation is not a characteristic feature of chronic inflammation. \r\n\r\nGranuloma formation, which consists of aggregates of epithelioid cells (not epithelial cells), giant cells, and lymphocytes surrounded by a rim of fibroblasts and collagen, is a possible outcome of chronic inflammation but is not mentioned in the given scenario.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 96.","responses":[{"text":"Abscess formation is the hallmark","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is predominantly characterized by a neutrophilic infiltrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It may result in granulomas composed of epithelial cells and blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It involves co-existence of inflammation, tissue repair and attempts at repair","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It always follows the acute inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13011,"text":"An individual sprains their ankle while hiking in the mountains and it becomes inflamed. Which of the following statements is most correct regarding this type of inflammation?","explanation":"**Inflammation** is a normal response of the body to injury or infection, and it is characterized by these classic signs and symptoms: **heat** (due to increased blood flow), **redness** (due to vasodilation), pain (caused by chemical mediators and pressure on nerve endings), and **swelling** (resulting from increased vascular permeability and fluid accumulation). These symptoms are part of the inflammatory process and are commonly observed in cases of sprains, where there is tissue damage and an inflammatory response is initiated to facilitate healing.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 12.","responses":[{"text":"It is characterized by the formation of granulomas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The cellular infiltrate comprises of macrophages and lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It resolves within twenty-four hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is not associated with tissue damage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is characterized heat, redness, pain and swelling","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13012,"text":"A 20-year-old man presents to the emergency room with complaints of developing a puffy face and difficulty breathing after eating prawns an hour ago. Which of the following inflammatory mediators is most likely responsible for this condition?","explanation":"**Histamine** is the most likely **inflammatory mediator** responsible for the symptoms described by the patient. Histamine is released from mast cells and basophils during allergic reactions, and it plays a crucial role in mediating immediate hypersensitivity reactions, such as allergic rhinitis, urticaria (hives), and anaphylaxis. \r\n\r\nHistamine causes **vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, bronchoconstriction**, and **smooth muscle contraction** in various organs. In the case of the patient's puffy face and difficulty breathing, histamine would be the primary mediator responsible for the symptoms.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 86.","responses":[{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotrienes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kinins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chemokines","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13013,"text":"Benign and malignant tumors have different behavior patterns. Which of the following properties unequivocally denotes a tumor as being malignant?","explanation":"The property that unequivocally denotes a tumor as being **malignant** is the **ability to metastasize**. **Metastasis** refers to the spread of cancer cells from the primary tumor to distant sites in the body. **Malignant tumors** have the capacity to invade surrounding tissues, enter blood vessels or lymphatics, and establish secondary tumors in distant organs or tissues. This ability to metastasize distinguishes malignant tumors from benign tumors, which do not invade or spread to distant sites. While other properties like local invasiveness and lack of encapsulation are often associated with malignancy, the definitive feature that classifies a tumor as malignant is its ability to metastasize.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 273, 274.","responses":[{"text":"Ability to metastasize","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Local invasiveness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Round margins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Encapsulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Slow growth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13014,"text":"Tumors are classified according to their degree of differentiation and can range from undifferentiated to well-differentiated. What is the term for lack of differentiation?","explanation":"The term for **lack of differentiation** in tumors is **anaplasia**. Anaplasia refers to the **loss of the normal cellular features** and organization seen in differentiated cells. In anaplastic tumors, the cells often have an abnormal appearance, with variations in size, shape, and nuclear characteristics. They may exhibit increased mitotic activity and have a loss of specialized functions. Anaplastic tumors are considered poorly differentiated and tend to be more aggressive and associated with a poorer prognosis compared to well-differentiated tumors.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 270.","responses":[{"text":"Dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atrophy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anaplasia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metaplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplasia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13015,"text":"A 30-year-old woman presents to the outpatient department with complaints of generalized weakness and shortness of breath on exertion for the past week. On examination she has pallor. Complete blood count showed a Hb of 6.0 g/dL, MCV: 55 fL, MCH: 18 pg, WBCs: 5000, platelets: 400,000. The blood smear shows a hypochromic and microcytic picture. What further investigation would you like to advise?","explanation":"In a patient presenting with **generalized weakness, shortness of breath on exertion**, and **pallor** along with laboratory findings of **low hemoglobin (Hb)**, **microcytic (small-sized) and hypochromic (pale)** red blood cells, the most appropriate next investigation to consider would be a **serum iron profile**.\r\n\r\nA serum iron profile typically includes measurements of serum iron, total iron-binding capacity (TIBC), and ferritin levels. These tests can help assess iron status and provide valuable information about the underlying cause of the patient's anemia.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the microcytic and hypochromic picture suggests iron deficiency anemia, which is one of the most common causes of anemia worldwide. The serum iron profile can help confirm the diagnosis and determine the severity and underlying etiology of the iron deficiency.\r\n\r\nAbdominal ultrasound, chest X-ray, and serum B12 and folate levels are not the most appropriate initial investigations for a patient with microcytic, hypochromic anemia suggestive of iron deficiency. While serum B12 and folate levels are important to assess in cases of macrocytic anemia, they are less relevant in microcytic anemia. Abdominal ultrasound and chest X-ray may be useful in specific clinical situations where there is suspicion of underlying pathology, but they are not the primary investigations for microcytic anemia.\r\n\r\nTherefore, a serum iron profile would provide valuable information to confirm the diagnosis and guide further management in this case.","reference":"Chaudhry HS, Kasarla MR. Microcytic hypochromic anemia. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 6, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470252/","responses":[{"text":"Chest X-Ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum iron profile","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum B12 level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum folate level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abdominal ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13016,"text":"A 35-year-old man presents to the outpatient clinic with complaints of exertion and breathlessness for the past three weeks. He was diagnosed with anemia. Laboratory investigations show normal iron levels. The physician suspects impaired ability of the bone marrow to produce normal red blood cells. What is the hallmark of this condition?","explanation":"**Folate deficiency** can lead to **megaloblastic anemia**, characterized by the presence of **macrocytic (larger than normal) red blood cells** with a reduced number of divisions in the bone marrow. Folate is necessary for DNA synthesis and cell division, and its deficiency can impair the production of normal red blood cells. Therefore, low folate levels can be associated with impaired bone marrow function and the development of anemia.\r\n\r\nLow ferritin levels are associated with iron deficiency anemia, as ferritin is an intracellular protein that stores iron. However, as mentioned earlier, the patient's laboratory investigations show normal iron levels, making low ferritin levels less likely in this case.\r\n\r\nNormochromic and normocytic cells are often associated with anemia of chronic disease, where red blood cells appear normal in color and size. However, without further information, it is difficult to determine if this is the specific hallmark of the condition in this patient.\r\n\r\nRinged sideroblasts are a finding typically associated with sideroblastic anemias, which are a group of disorders characterized by abnormal iron metabolism in the bone marrow. Ringed sideroblasts are red blood cell precursors in the bone marrow that contain iron granules in a ring-like distribution around the nucleus. Since the laboratory investigations in this patient show normal iron levels, ringed sideroblasts are less likely to be present.\r\n\r\nDecreased myeloid precursors on bone marrow would suggest a disorder affecting the production of not only red blood cells but also other blood cell lineages, such as white blood cells and platelets. Without further information, it is difficult to determine if this is the case for the patient described.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 651, 654.","responses":[{"text":"Ringed sideroblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased myeloid precursors on bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low folate levels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Low ferritin levels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normochromic and normocytic cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13042,"text":"A 10-year-old boy presents to the pediatric outpatient department with complaints of fever and gum bleeding for the past week. A complete blood count showed pancytopenia and reticulocytopenia. The bone marrow biopsy showed hypocellular marrow. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"Based on the clinical presentation and laboratory findings described, the most likely diagnosis in this case is **aplastic anemia**.\r\n\r\n**Aplastic anemia** is a condition characterized by a deficiency of all types of blood cells (pancytopenia) due to the **failure of the bone marrow** to produce an adequate number of blood cells. It can result from a variety of causes, including autoimmune disorders, viral infections, exposure to certain medications or toxins, and inherited genetic disorders. In this case, the patient's **pancytopenia, reticulocytopenia**, and **hypocellular** bone marrow biopsy findings are consistent with **aplastic anemia**.\r\n\r\nAcute leukemia typically presents with symptoms such as fatigue, pallor, bleeding, and organomegaly. Laboratory findings in acute leukemia typically show increased blast cells in the peripheral blood and bone marrow, rather than pancytopenia and hypocellular marrow as seen in this case.\r\n\r\nMyeloproliferative disorders are characterized by excessive production of one or more blood cell lineages, such as red blood cells, platelets, or white blood cells. Pancytopenia and hypocellular marrow are not consistent with a myeloproliferative disorder.\r\n\r\nMyelodysplastic syndrome is a disorder characterized by abnormal development and maturation of blood cells in the bone marrow. It typically presents with cytopenias and dysplastic changes in the bone marrow, but the pancytopenia and hypocellular marrow seen in this case are more indicative of aplastic anemia.\r\n\r\nStorage cell disorders, such as Gaucher disease or Niemann-Pick disease, are genetic disorders characterized by the accumulation of specific substances within cells. These disorders usually present with specific clinical manifestations and laboratory findings related to the storage material, which are not described in this case.","reference":"Keohane EM. Acquired aplastic anemia. Clinical Laboratory Science: Journal of the American Society for Medical Technology. Published 2004. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15314891/","responses":[{"text":"Myelodysplastic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Myeloproliferative disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Storage cell disorder","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute leukemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13049,"text":"A 25-year-old man was brought to the emergency room after his motorcycle slipped and he got several abrasive injuries. He complained of an excruciating burning sensation on the injured sites with minimal bleeding. Which of the following mechanism is most likely to reduce blood loss from his wounds?","explanation":"When tissue injury occurs, the coagulation cascade is initiated to form a blood clot and prevent excessive bleeding. **Coagulation factors**, such as fibrinogen, prothrombin, and various clotting factors, are activated to form a fibrin meshwork that stabilizes the clot. This process involves a series of enzymatic reactions that ultimately lead to the **conversion of fibrinogen to fibrin**.\r\n\r\nPlatelet aggregation also plays a role in the formation of a blood clot, but in this case, the minimal bleeding suggests that platelet aggregation alone may not be sufficient to control bleeding.\r\n\r\nThrombin activation is an important step in the coagulation cascade, but it is not the primary mechanism that reduces blood loss from wounds.\r\n\r\nVasoconstriction, the constriction of blood vessels, can help limit blood flow to the injured area, but it is not the main mechanism responsible for reducing blood loss in this context.\r\n\r\nProtein C activation primarily acts as an anticoagulant and helps regulate the coagulation process, but its activation is not directly involved in reducing blood loss from wounds.\r\n\r\nTherefore, among the given options, the activation of coagulation factors is the most likely mechanism to **reduce blood loss** from the wounds.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, et al. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed., Elsevier, 2020: 118.","responses":[{"text":"Protein C activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulation factors activation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet aggregation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13050,"text":"The blood remains in circulation because of a balance between procoagulant and anticoagulant forces. Proteolytic destruction of which of the following by the protein C inhibits the process of coagulation?","explanation":"**Proteolytic destruction** of activated **factor V** and **factor VIII** by **protein C** inhibits the process of coagulation. Protein C is a **natural anticoagulant** protein that works in conjunction with its cofactor **protein S** to inactivate **factors Va and VIIIa**, which are important for the amplification of the coagulation cascade. By cleaving activated factor V and factor VIII, protein C helps to downregulate the coagulation process and prevent excessive clot formation. This mechanism serves as an important negative feedback loop to maintain the balance between coagulation and anticoagulation in the bloodstream.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 483.","responses":[{"text":"Activated factor I and factor IV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor V and factor VIII","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor X and factor XI","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor VII and factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activated factor II and factor III","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13051,"text":"A 49-year-old bed-bound man feels shortness of breath and dies within a few minutes. Autopsy reveals a saddle embolus in the pulmonary artery. Which of the following events could likely have been his cause of death?","explanation":"A **saddle embolus** in the **pulmonary artery** refers to a large blood clot that obstructs the main pulmonary artery or its major branches, significantly impeding blood flow to the lungs. This obstruction can lead to a **sudden increase in pulmonary vascular resistance**, causing acute strain on the right side of the heart.\r\n\r\nThe increased resistance in the pulmonary circulation can result in acute right ventricular failure, leading to a rapid decrease in cardiac output and systemic hypotension. The compromised cardiac function can cause a sudden onset of severe shortness of breath, cardiovascular collapse, and eventual death.\r\n\r\nWhile pulmonary infarction can occur as a result of the embolus, the primary cause of death in this case is the 8*acute cardiac failure** resulting from the obstructive saddle embolus in the pulmonary artery.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 9th ed. Elsevier Saunders; 2015: 127.","responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary congestion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiac failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary infarction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericarditis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13052,"text":"A 62-year-old woman is diagnosed with breast cancer, which has metastasized to lymph nodes. Cancer cells often acquire growth autonomy because of mutation in genes that encode components of signaling pathways downstream of growth factor receptors. Which of the following is an important component of oncoproteins in the category of signaling molecules?","explanation":"**HER2**, also known as **ERBB2**, is a receptor tyrosine kinase that belongs to the **epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFR)** family. It plays a critical role in cell growth, proliferation, and survival. Amplification or overexpression of the HER2 gene leads to increased HER2 protein levels on the cell surface, resulting in excessive activation of downstream signaling pathways.\r\n\r\nMutations or amplification of the HER2 gene are frequently observed in breast cancer and are associated with aggressive tumor behavior and poor prognosis. The overexpression of HER2 leads to dysregulation of cell growth and contributes to the development and progression of **breast cancer**.\r\n\r\nWhile other answer choices such as the Retinoblastoma (RB) protein, PF3, and Platelet-derived growth factor (PDGF) can also have roles in cancer development and progression, HER2 is specifically known for its involvement in breast cancer and is targeted in anti-HER2 therapies.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 24.","responses":[{"text":"PF3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RAS gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet-derived growth factor (PDGF)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retinoblastoma (RB) protein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13053,"text":"A researcher is conducting a research study to find the prevalence of diabetes mellitus in Karachi city. Which of the following epidemiological study design should be undertaken for this research","explanation":"For the research study to find the **prevalence of diabetes mellitus** in Karachi city, the most appropriate epidemiological study design would be a **cross-sectional study**.\r\n\r\nA **cross-sectional study** involves collecting data from a population at a specific point in time to determine the **prevalence** of a disease or condition. In this study, the researcher would select a representative sample of individuals from Karachi city and collect data on their diabetes status and relevant risk factors at a single time point. The prevalence of diabetes can then be calculated as the number of individuals with diabetes divided by the total number of individuals in the sample.\r\n\r\nA cross-sectional study provides a snapshot of the disease prevalence in a population at a specific time, allowing for the estimation of disease burden. It is suitable for determining the proportion of individuals with a specific condition (diabetes mellitus) in a population and can also explore associations between risk factors and disease prevalence.","reference":"Cross-sectional studies - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed December 7, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/cross-sectional-studies","responses":[{"text":"Case control study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross sectional study","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental study","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13054,"text":"A researcher is conducting a research study to find the incidence of diabetes mellitus in Karachi city. Which of the following epidemiological study design should be undertaken for this research?","explanation":"For the research study to find the **incidence of diabetes mellitus** in Karachi city, the most appropriate epidemiological study design would be a **cohort study**.\r\n\r\nA **cohort study** involves selecting a group of individuals **without the disease of interest** (in this case, diabetes mellitus) and following them over time to determine the **incidence of the disease**. In this study, the researcher would identify a population in Karachi city without diabetes mellitus and track them prospectively to assess the development of diabetes over a specific period. The researcher would collect information on risk factors, such as age, lifestyle, genetics, etc., and follow up with the participants to determine who develops diabetes. By comparing the incidence of diabetes among different groups with varying risk factors, the researcher can analyze associations and calculate the incidence rate.\r\n\r\nA **cohort study** is suitable for examining the relationship between exposure and disease development and allows for the calculation of incidence rates and relative risk.","reference":"Cross-sectional studies - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed December 7, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/cross-sectional-studies","responses":[{"text":"Case control study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort study","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross sectional study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental study","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13055,"text":"A lecturer was teaching his student a very simple form of epidemiological study designs. He explained this type of study is based on a unique condition or rare disease reported by a consultant in a patient. Which of the following study designs is the lecturer referring to?","explanation":"A **case report** is a **descriptive study design** that focuses on a **single** or a **small number of cases with a unique condition, rare disease**, or **unusual presentation**. It typically involves detailed clinical information about the patient, including medical history, symptoms, physical examination findings, diagnostic tests, and treatment outcomes. Case reports are often used to document and share information about rare or novel conditions, unexpected treatment responses, or adverse events. They provide valuable insights and can generate hypotheses for further research. However, case reports alone cannot establish causal relationships or provide strong evidence, as they lack comparison groups and statistical analysis.","reference":"Guidelines to writing a clinical case report. Heart Views : The Official Journal of the Gulf Heart Association. Published 2017. Accessed December 7, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5686928/","responses":[{"text":"Case control study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cross sectional study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Randomized control trial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case report","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13056,"text":"A group of students was analyzing their research data set. The data showed that the frequency distribution of age of the study participants had a long tail on the right-hand side of the curve than on the left side. Which of the following describes this frequency distribution?","explanation":"The frequency distribution described, with a long tail on the right-hand side of the curve, is indicative of a **skewed distribution**.\r\n\r\n**Skewness** refers to the asymmetry of a frequency distribution. In a skewed distribution, the data is not symmetrically distributed around the mean. If the tail of the distribution extends towards the right side (higher values), it is referred to as a right-skewed or positively skewed distribution. Conversely, if the tail extends towards the left side (lower values), it is referred to as a left-skewed or negatively skewed distribution.\r\n\r\nIn this case, with a **long tail on the right-hand side**, the frequency distribution is **right-skewed**.","reference":"Skewed distribution - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed December 7, 2022. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/mathematics/skewed-distribution","responses":[{"text":"Standard","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gaussian","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skewed","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Precise","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13057,"text":"A professor of epidemiology was teaching epidemiological study designs to his students. He was emphasizing how to follow up with the patients and how to reduce loss to follow up in an observational study. The professor is teaching his students about which of the following epidemiological study designs?","explanation":"In a **cohort study**, a group of individuals with the exposure of interest (the exposed group) and a group without the exposure of interest (the unexposed group) are followed over time to determine the **incidence of the outcome**. The professor's emphasis on **follow-up** and reducing loss to follow-up indicates that he is teaching the cohort study design, which requires long-term follow-up of participants to gather data on the development of the outcome.\r\n\r\nCross-sectional study: In a cross-sectional study, data is collected at a single point in time to assess the prevalence of a disease or exposure in a population.\r\nCase series study: A case series study involves the collection and presentation of detailed information on a group of patients with a similar diagnosis or outcome.\r\nExperimental study: In an experimental study, participants are assigned to different groups, and the investigator manipulates an intervention or exposure to determine its effect on the outcome.\r\nCase-control study: In a case-control study, individuals with the outcome of interest (cases) and individuals without the outcome (controls) are identified, and exposure history is compared between the two groups to assess the association between exposure and outcome.","reference":"Barrett D, Noble H. What are cohort studies? Evidence-Based Nursing. Published October 1, 2019. Accessed December 8, 2022. https://ebn.bmj.com/content/22/4/95","responses":[{"text":"Cross sectional study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Experimental study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case series study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Case control study","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cohort study","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13058,"text":"Which of the following terms best describes the occurrence of a disease in a community or region with a frequency clearly in excess of normal expectancy?","explanation":"An **epidemic** refers to the rapid spread of a disease within a population or geographical area, resulting in a higher number of cases than expected. It indicates a sudden increase in the incidence of a particular disease beyond what is typically seen in that population or area. Epidemics can be localized or widespread, affecting a specific community, region, or even multiple countries.\r\n\r\nExotic refers to a disease that is foreign or not native to a particular region or population.\r\nEndemic describes the constant presence or usual prevalence of a disease within a specific geographic area or population.\r\nPandemic refers to a global outbreak of a disease, affecting a large number of people worldwide.\r\nSporadic refers to isolated cases of a disease occurring occasionally and without any pattern or regularity.","reference":"https://www.cdc.gov/csels/dsepd/ss1978/lesson1/section11.html","responses":[{"text":"Exotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13059,"text":"Which of the following terms best describes the disease causation model that can be used for explaining the mechanism of chronic disease occurrence like diabetes and heart disease with multiple risk factors?","explanation":"The term that best describes the disease causation model used to explain the mechanism of chronic disease occurrence with multiple risk factors is the **web of causation**. The web of causation model recognizes that chronic diseases, such as diabetes and heart disease, are multifactorial in nature and result from the complex interaction of multiple risk factors. These risk factors can include genetic predisposition, lifestyle factors (such as diet and physical activity), environmental factors, and social determinants of health. The web of causation model illustrates how these various factors interact and contribute to the development of chronic diseases, emphasizing the interconnectedness and complexity of the causal pathways involved.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood Module; Subject: Community medicine; Topic: Origin and determinants of disease; Sub-topic: The web of causation.","responses":[{"text":"Epidemiological triangle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Web of causation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Determinants of disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dynamics of disease transmission","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wheel of causation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13060,"text":"EPI Program in Pakistan offers immunization to young children against various endemic infectious diseases including polio, diphtheria, tetanus, and measles. The routine immunization of young children is an example of which of the following?","explanation":"The **routine immunization** of young children is an example of **primary prevention**. Primary prevention aims to **prevent the occurrence of a disease** or condition before it occurs or becomes established. In this case, immunization is administered to young children before they are exposed to specific infectious diseases, with the goal of providing long-term protection and preventing the occurrence of these diseases.","reference":"Kisling LA, M Das J. Prevention strategies. StatPearls. Published 2022. Accessed December 7, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537222/","responses":[{"text":"Selective prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary prevention","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Outbreak control","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertiary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13448,"text":"A 15-year-old patient is diagnosed with a connective tissue disorder. The disorder involves a protein called fibrillin, encoded by the FBN1 gene that maps to chromosomal locus 15q21. Mutations in the FBN1 gene are found in all patients suffering from which of the following diseases?","explanation":"Mutations in the **FBN1 gene** are found in patients suffering from **Marfan syndrome**. Marfan syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the connective tissue, primarily involving the cardiovascular system, skeletal system, and eyes. **Fibrillin**, encoded by the FBN1 gene, is a major component of the extracellular matrix and plays a crucial role in maintaining the structural integrity of connective tissues. Mutations in the FBN1 gene lead to abnormal fibrillin production or function, resulting in the clinical manifestations of Marfan syndrome.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 148, 149.","responses":[{"text":"Severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ehlers-Danlos syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Marfan syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tay-Sachs disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13449,"text":"A 33-year-old patient is diagnosed with leukemia. A fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) report of the DNA analysis of the tumor cells has the term \"Philadelphia chromosome\". Which of the following molecular events leads to the formation of this chromosome?","explanation":"The formation of the **Philadelphia chromosome** in leukemia is due to a specific molecular event called **translocation**. The Philadelphia chromosome results from a **reciprocal translocation between chromosome 9 and chromosome 22**, specifically the **translocation of the ABL proto-oncogene** from chromosome 9 to the BCR gene on chromosome 22. This translocation, also known as the t(9;22) translocation, leads to the production of a fusion gene called BCR-ABL, which is associated with chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) and a subset of acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL).","reference":"Asif M, Hussain A, Wali A, et al. Molecular, cytogenetic, and hematological analysis of chronic myeloid leukemia patients and discovery of two novel translocations. Analytical Cellular Pathology (Amsterdam). Published August 12, 2021. Accessed December 12, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8378985/","responses":[{"text":"Trinucleotide repeats","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Point mutation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duplication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Translocation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Deletion","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13450,"text":"A 30-year-old man is brought to the emergency room with a complaint of severe chest pain for the past hour. He is diagnosed with unstable angina secondary to familial hypercholesterolemia. Familial hypercholesterolemia is an autosomal dominant disorder. If an affected person marries an unaffected person, what are the chances of the offspring developing the disorder?","explanation":"**Familial hypercholesterolemia** is an **autosomal dominant disorder**, which means that an affected individual has a 50% chance of passing on the condition to each of their offspring. If an **affected person** marries an **unaffected person**, the chances of the offspring developing the disorder would be **one in two, or 50%**.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 144.","responses":[{"text":"One in five","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"One in ten","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"One in two","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cent percent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"One in four","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13451,"text":"The complement system is a system of about 20 different proteins which perform important defensive functions in the body. there are three pathways of complement activation, classical pathway, alternate pathway, and mannose-binding lecithin pathway. These pathways merge at which of the following stages?","explanation":"The three pathways of complement activation, namely the classical pathway, alternative pathway, and lectin pathway, converge at the **activation of C3b**. C3b is a central component of the complement system and plays a crucial role in the **opsonization of pathogens, phagocytosis**, and the **formation of the membrane attack complex (MAC)** to destroy target cells. Once C3b is activated, it initiates a cascade of reactions that lead to the formation of MAC and the subsequent destruction of the target cell.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 537.","responses":[{"text":"Activation of C7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of C5a","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Formation of the membrane attack complex (MAC)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of C1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Activation of C3b","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":13452,"text":"An approach to psychology focuses on observable behavior that can be measured objectively. It implies that our behavior is related to our environment and we can modify our behavior by modifying our environment. Which of the following paradigms includes this approach?","explanation":"The approach that includes the focus on **observable behavior**, its measurement, and the belief that behavior is influenced by the environment is the **behavioral approach**. The behavioral approach emphasizes the importance of studying and understanding behavior in terms of observable actions, rather than focusing on internal mental processes. It suggests that behavior can be modified and changed by modifying the environment and the external stimuli that influence behavior.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module; Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Learning and behavior; Sub-topic: Behaviorism.","responses":[{"text":"Psychodynamic approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cognitive approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Humanistic approach","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Behavioral approach","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Learning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13453,"text":"A type of learning in which a neutral stimulus is presented repeatedly with one that reflexively elicits a particular response so that the neutral stimulus eventually the response itself, is known as classical conditioning. After a conditioned response becomes extinct, the response can re-emerge after a while has passed with no further conditioning. What is this event referred to?","explanation":"**Spontaneous recovery** is the reappearance of a **previously extinguished conditioned respons**e after a period of time has passed without any further conditioning. It occurs even without the presentation of the conditioned stimulus or any additional training. This phenomenon suggests that the association between the conditioned stimulus and the conditioned response is not completely erased during extinction and can be temporarily restored.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module; Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Learning and behavior: Sub-topic: Classical conditioning-spontaneous recovery.","responses":[{"text":"Stimulant generalization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Operant conditioning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Learning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spontaneous recovery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Extinction","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13455,"text":"A 10-year-old boy has a history of easy bruising and hemarthrosis. He is diagnosed with hemophilia B. Which of the following factors is deficient in hemophilia B?","explanation":"In **hemophilia B**, also known as Christmas disease, there is a deficiency of **factor IX**. **Factor IX** is a clotting factor involved in the **intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade**. Its deficiency results in impaired blood clotting and prolonged bleeding. This genetic disorder is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern, primarily affecting males. Hemophilia B is characterized by symptoms such as easy bruising, spontaneous bleeding, and hemarthrosis (bleeding into the joints).","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 669.","responses":[{"text":"Factor X","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor XII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor IX","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VIII","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Factor VII","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13479,"text":"One of the psychological theories of child development refers to developing relationships between the child and significant others in the child's life, especially the mother. Early internalized relationships affect children as they become adults and develop their own personalities. In adult life, a transitional phenomenon can be expressed as a means of playing with one's own ideas and developing creative and new thoughts. What is this theory known as?","explanation":"**Object relations theory** is a psychodynamic theory that focuses on the relationships individuals form with others, particularly in early childhood. It emphasizes the role of these early relationships, especially with the mother or primary caregiver, in shaping the individual's psychological development and sense of self.\r\n\r\nAccording to object relations theory, the quality of early relationships and the internalized representations of significant others, referred to as \"objects,\" influence the individual's interpersonal relationships and self-perception throughout life. These internalized object relations serve as a template for future relationships and play a role in the development of one's personality and sense of identity.\r\n\r\nObject relations theory also recognizes the importance of transitional phenomena, which refer to the capacity to creatively play with ideas and engage in symbolic thought. This transitional space allows for the exploration of new thoughts, feelings, and creative expressions.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module; Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Child development; Sub-topic: Object relation psychology.","responses":[{"text":"Object relation psychology","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Relational psychoanalysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Self psychology","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Drive theory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ego psychology","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":13485,"text":"In one of the stages of cognitive development, the child learns to use language and symbols to represent things but does not comprehend certain operations (like logically separating, combining, and transforming information). Thinking is still egocentric: having difficulty in taking the viewpoint of others. This stage has not yet attained conservation in terms of the understanding that the amount of a substance remains the same even when its form is changed. What is this stage known as?","explanation":"The stage described in the question is known as the **preoperational stage**, according to Jean Piaget's theory of cognitive development. This stage typically occurs in children between the ages of 2 and 7 years. During this stage, children develop the ability to use language and symbols to represent objects and events. They engage in pretend play and begin to understand the concept of past and future.\r\n\r\nHowever, children in the preoperational stage have limitations in their thinking. They are still egocentric, meaning they struggle to take the perspective of others and tend to view the world solely from their own point of view. They also lack the concept of conservation, which is the understanding that the amount of a substance remains the same despite changes in its appearance or arrangement.\r\n\r\nThe concrete operational stage, which follows the preoperational stage, is when children acquire the ability to think logically, understand conservation, and grasp the concept of reversibility. This stage usually occurs around 7 to 11 years of age.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Blood module, Subject: Behavioral sciences; Topic: Child development;  Sub-topic: The preoperational stage.","responses":[{"text":"The concrete operational stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The sensorimotor stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The social development stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The formal operational stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The preoperational stage","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15335,"text":"Which of the following conditions is not an example of shock associated with systemic inflammation?","explanation":"**Myocardial infarction** is not typically considered an example of shock associated with systemic inflammation. Myocardial infarction occurs due to a blockage in the blood vessels supplying the heart muscle, leading to inadequate blood flow and oxygen supply to the heart. While myocardial infarction can lead to systemic inflammatory response and complications such as heart failure, it is not primarily characterized by shock associated with systemic inflammation.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, fungal or microbial infections, burns, pancreatitis, and trauma can all trigger systemic inflammatory responses that may result in shock. These conditions can lead to the release of pro-inflammatory mediators, vascular dilation, increased capillary permeability, and subsequent hypotension, which are characteristic features of shock associated with systemic inflammation.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 135.","responses":[{"text":"Myocardial Infarction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Burns","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancreatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trauma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fingal or microbial infection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15337,"text":"A 45-year-old woman develops swelling in her lower legs and feet after standing for long periods at the end of her 8-hour shift with no associated pain or erythema. There is no swelling at the beginning of her day. Her kidney and liver are also in healthy condition. What is the probable diagnosis for her condition?","explanation":"**Heart failure** can lead to impaired pumping function of the heart, resulting in reduced cardiac output and increased venous pressure. The increased venous pressure leads to fluid accumulation in the dependent areas, such as the lower extremities.\r\n\r\nHeart failure can be caused by various factors, including coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular heart disease, and cardiomyopathies. It is important to evaluate the patient for signs and symptoms of heart failure, such as dyspnea, fatigue, orthopnea, and peripheral edema.\r\n\r\nOther causes of lower extremity swelling, such as renal insufficiency, arthritis, nephritic syndrome, and gout, would typically present with additional symptoms and findings specific to those conditions. In this case, the absence of pain, erythema, and involvement of kidney and liver function helps differentiate heart failure as the likely cause of the swelling.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 117.","responses":[{"text":"Gout","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal insufficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased hydrostatic pressure due to heart failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephritic syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15338,"text":"A 55-year-old man presents to the outpatient department with stomach issues. On examination, he has massive splenomegaly seen (crossing the umbilicus). Which of the following conditions is he most likely to have?","explanation":"**Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML)** is a myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by the clonal expansion of myeloid cells, particularly granulocytes, in the bone marrow and peripheral blood. Splenomegaly is a common feature of CML and can be massive, as seen in this case.\r\n\r\nIn CML, the abnormal proliferation of myeloid cells is driven by the Philadelphia chromosome, a genetic abnormality resulting from a translocation between chromosomes 9 and 22. This translocation leads to the formation of the BCR-ABL fusion gene, which encodes a constitutively active tyrosine kinase protein. The excessive production of myeloid cells leads to an increase in spleen size.\r\n\r\nOther symptoms of CML include fatigue, weight loss, night sweats, and abdominal discomfort. The diagnosis is confirmed by the presence of the Philadelphia chromosome or BCR-ABL fusion gene detected through cytogenetic or molecular testing.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 622.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic myeloid leukemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15339,"text":"Which of the following is used to normalize blood flow by fibrinolysis of fibrin?","explanation":"**Plasmin** is an enzyme that plays a key role in **fibrinolysis**, which is the process of breaking down fibrin, the protein meshwork that forms blood clots. Plasmin acts to dissolve the fibrin network, leading to the breakdown of blood clots and normalization of blood flow. It is derived from plasminogen, an inactive precursor, through the action of tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) or other plasminogen activators. Plasminogen activators convert plasminogen into plasmin, which then degrades fibrin into soluble products.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 484.","responses":[{"text":"Plasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Protein C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warfarin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15340,"text":"Deficiency of which of the following options can lead to an accumulation of homocysteine?","explanation":"Deficiency of **folic acid** can lead to an accumulation of **homocysteine**. Folic acid is a B-vitamin that is essential for the synthesis and metabolism of DNA, as well as the production of red blood cells. It plays a crucial role in the conversion of homocysteine to methionine through a process called remethylation.\r\n\r\nWhen folic acid is deficient, the remethylation process is impaired, leading to the accumulation of homocysteine in the blood. Elevated levels of homocysteine are associated with increased risk of cardiovascular disease and other health conditions.\r\n\r\nFolic acid deficiency can occur due to inadequate dietary intake, malabsorption disorders, or increased demand during periods of rapid growth or pregnancy. Supplementation with folic acid or consumption of foods rich in folate, such as leafy green vegetables, citrus fruits, and legumes, can help prevent deficiency and the associated accumulation of homocysteine.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 655.","responses":[{"text":"Biotin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Riboflavin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Folic acid","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15341,"text":"Which of the following helps in the absorption of iron?","explanation":"**Ascorbic acid** (also known as **Vitamin C**) is involved in the **absorption of iron**. It **enhances** the absorption of non-heme iron, which is the form of iron found in plant-based foods and iron supplements. Ascorbic acid forms a complex with iron, reducing it from the ferric (Fe3+) to the ferrous (Fe2+) state, which is more easily absorbed in the intestines. It also helps to solubilize iron and prevent its oxidation. Therefore, ascorbic acid plays a crucial role in promoting the absorption of dietary iron and preventing iron deficiency anemia.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 381.","responses":[{"text":"Calcium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascorbic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niacin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15342,"text":"Which immunoglobulin helps in opsonization?","explanation":"The immunoglobulin that plays a significant role in **opsonization** is **IgG**. Opsonization is the process by which particles such as bacteria or other pathogens are marked for destruction by immune cells. IgG antibodies bind to specific antigens on the surface of these particles, effectively \"tagging\" them for recognition by phagocytes, such as macrophages and neutrophils.\r\n\r\nOnce bound to the pathogen, IgG antibodies enhance the efficiency of phagocytosis by promoting the attachment of phagocytes to the antibody-coated surface. This opsonization process improves the recognition and engulfment of the pathogen, facilitating its destruction by the immune system.\r\n\r\nIgG is the most abundant immunoglobulin in the bloodstream and is capable of activating the complement system and crossing the placenta to provide passive immunity to the fetus. Its opsonizing properties contribute to the elimination of pathogens and play a crucial role in the body's defense against infections.","reference":"Opsonin - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed March 7, 2023. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/opsonin","responses":[{"text":"IgG","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"IgD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgM","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15343,"text":"Which of the following options is the functionally active form of folic acid?","explanation":"The functionally active form of folic acid is **tetrahydrofolic acid (THF)**. Folic acid is a vitamin that is converted to its active form through a series of enzymatic reactions in the body. THF is involved in one-carbon transfer reactions, which are essential for DNA synthesis, amino acid metabolism, and other cellular processes.\r\n\r\nFolic acid is initially converted to dihydrofolic acid and then further reduced to THF by the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase. THF is then converted to various derivatives, such as 5-methyltetrahydrofolic acid, which is involved in the methylation of homocysteine to methionine.\r\n\r\nTHF functions as a carrier of one-carbon units, which are necessary for the synthesis of nucleotides and amino acids. It participates in the synthesis of DNA and RNA, making it crucial for cell division and growth. Deficiency of THF can lead to impaired DNA synthesis and cell division, resulting in megaloblastic anemia and other manifestations of folate deficiency.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 267.","responses":[{"text":"Tetrahydrofolic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monoglutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5-methyltetrahydrofolic acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyglutamate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15344,"text":"Which is the characteristic morphology of red blood cells seen in megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":"In megaloblastic anemia, which is typically caused by deficiencies in vitamin B12 or folic acid, the characteristic morphology of red blood cells includes **macro-ovalocytes**. Macro-ovalocytes are abnormally large and oval-shaped red blood cells.\r\n\r\nNormally, red blood cells are round and of uniform size. However, in megaloblastic anemia, impaired DNA synthesis and delayed maturation of red blood cell precursors result in the production of larger and more oval-shaped cells.\r\n\r\nThe presence of macro-ovalocytes can be observed on a peripheral blood smear, which is a microscopic examination of a blood sample. This finding is an important diagnostic clue for megaloblastic anemia. Other features that may be seen in megaloblastic anemia include hypersegmented neutrophils, anemia, and abnormalities in other blood cell lineages.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 651.","responses":[{"text":"Heinz bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersegmented neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle-shaped red blood cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macro-ovalocyte","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Central pallor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15345,"text":"Which is the characteristic morphology of white blood cells seen in megaloblastic anemia?","explanation":"In megaloblastic anemia, which is typically caused by deficiencies in vitamin B12 or folic acid, the characteristic morphology of white blood cells includes **hypersegmented neutrophils**. Neutrophils are a type of white blood cell that plays a crucial role in the immune response and defense against infections.\r\n\r\nHypersegmented neutrophils are identified by the presence of more than five nuclear lobes. In normal individuals, neutrophils typically have two to five lobes. However, in megaloblastic anemia, due to impaired DNA synthesis and delayed nuclear maturation, the neutrophils exhibit hypersegmentation.\r\n\r\nThe appearance of hypersegmented neutrophils serves as an important clue in the diagnosis of megaloblastic anemia. Other findings in megaloblastic anemia may include macrocytic red blood cells, anemia, and abnormalities in other blood cell lineages.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 651.","responses":[{"text":"Megaovalocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Heinz bodies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypersegmented neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polymorphonuclear neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophilic stippling","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15348,"text":"Which of the following fluids is similar in electrolyte and water fraction to plasma?","explanation":"The **interstitial fluid** is the fluid that surrounds and bathes the cells in the body's tissues. It is similar in composition to plasma, the fluid component of blood, in terms of its electrolyte and water fractions. The interstitial fluid is derived from plasma as it passes through the capillary walls and into the spaces between cells.\r\n\r\nThe composition of interstitial fluid is regulated by various mechanisms to maintain its similarity to plasma. It contains ions such as sodium, potassium, chloride, bicarbonate, and calcium, as well as nutrients, waste products, and oxygen. The exchange of substances between the interstitial fluid and the cells allows for the delivery of nutrients and removal of waste products.\r\n\r\nWhile other fluids listed, such as amniotic fluid, cerebrospinal fluid, intracellular fluid, and synovial fluid, have their unique compositions and functions, interstitial fluid closely resembles plasma in its electrolyte and water composition.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 307.","responses":[{"text":"Synovial fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amniotic fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial fluid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebrospinal fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intracellular fluid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15350,"text":"Which of the following corresponds to the percentage of HbA2 in adults?","explanation":"In adults, the percentage of **hemoglobin A2 (HbA2)** typically ranges from **2% to 3%**. HbA2 is a specific form of hemoglobin composed of two alpha chains and two delta chains. It is one of the normal variants of hemoglobin found in adult red blood cells.\r\n\r\nThe measurement of HbA2 is important in the diagnosis of certain hemoglobinopathies, particularly beta-thalassemia. Increased levels of HbA2 can be seen in individuals with beta-thalassemia trait or other forms of beta-thalassemia.\r\n\r\nThe reference range for HbA2 may vary slightly depending on the laboratory and the population being tested. However, the range of 2% to 3% is commonly accepted as the normal range for HbA2 in adults.","reference":"Hemoglobin electrophoresis. ucsfhealth.org. Accessed March 7, 2023. https://www.ucsfhealth.org/Medical Tests/003639.","responses":[{"text":"6-7%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1-5%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2-3%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1.5-1.9%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3.5-4.5%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15390,"text":"At which of the following stages should a RhoGAM be administered to prevent erythroblastosis fetalis?","explanation":"**RhoGAM (anti-D immunoglobulin)** is administered to prevent erythroblastosis fetalis, a condition where the mother's immune system produces antibodies against the Rh antigen on the red blood cells of the fetus. The administration of RhoGAM is crucial when the mother is Rh-negative and the fetus is Rh-positive.\r\n\r\nThe recommended timing for administering RhoGAM is during the **28th to 30th week of pregnancy**, specifically at around 28 weeks. This is because there is a risk of mixing of fetal and maternal blood during delivery, which can sensitize the mother's immune system to the Rh antigen and lead to antibody production. By administering RhoGAM at this stage, any fetal Rh-positive red blood cells that enter the maternal circulation are cleared before the mother's immune system has a chance to mount an immune response.\r\n\r\nAdditional doses of RhoGAM may be given within 72 hours after delivery if the newborn is confirmed to be Rh-positive. This postpartum dose ensures clearance of any fetal red blood cells that may have entered the maternal circulation during childbirth.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 474.","responses":[{"text":"One week before pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7th month of pregnancy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"After birth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Few weeks after birth","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"One month after birth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15391,"text":"Which of the following is the site of production of 90% erythropoietin?","explanation":"The **kidney** is the primary site of production of erythropoietin, responsible for about 90% of its production in the body. Erythropoietin is a hormone produced by specialized cells in the kidney called interstitial fibroblasts, located in the peritubular capillaries of the renal cortex and outer medulla.\r\n\r\nErythropoietin production is regulated by the oxygen-sensing mechanism in the kidneys. When the oxygen levels in the blood decrease, such as during anemia or in response to hypoxia, the interstitial fibroblasts detect the low oxygen levels and respond by increasing the production and release of erythropoietin into the bloodstream. Erythropoietin then stimulates the bone marrow to increase red blood cell production, leading to the correction of anemia and improved oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood.\r\n\r\nWhile the bone marrow is the site of red blood cell production, it is the kidney that plays a central role in regulating erythropoiesis through the production of erythropoietin.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 442.","responses":[{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kidney","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15392,"text":"In which of the following organs do blood islands first form first?","explanation":"Blood islands first form in the **yolk sac or umbilical vesicle** during embryonic development. The yolk sac is an extraembryonic membrane that plays a crucial role in the early development of blood cells. It contains a network of blood vessels where the process of hematopoiesis initiates.\r\n\r\nDuring the third week of embryonic development, specialized cells called angioblasts migrate to the yolk sac and aggregate to form the blood islands. These blood islands consist of a central core of hematopoietic cells surrounded by endothelial cells that form primitive blood vessels. The hematopoietic cells within the blood islands undergo differentiation and give rise to various blood cell lineages, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.\r\n\r\nAs development progresses, hematopoiesis shifts to other organs such as the liver, spleen, thymus, and eventually the bone marrow. However, the yolk sac serves as the initial site of blood island formation and plays a critical role in the early establishment of the hematopoietic system.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 62.","responses":[{"text":"Yolk sac or umbilical vesicle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15393,"text":"A 50-year-old woman is admitted to the hospital after a transient ischemic attack. She has been bedridden for the past 4 days and develops sudden onset pain and edema in her right leg. Ultrasound confirms the presence of deep venous thrombosis. Which of the following is the most likely cause of her condition?","explanation":"The most likely cause of **deep venous thrombosis (DVT)** in this patient is **immobilization**. Immobilization leads to a condition called venous stasis, where blood flow in the veins becomes sluggish or stagnant. This stagnant blood flow predisposes the patient to the formation of blood clots.\r\n\r\nProlonged immobilization, such as being bedridden for several days, can disrupt the normal circulation of blood in the veins, especially in the lower extremities. Reduced muscle activity and lack of movement impede the pumping action of the calf muscles, which normally assist in propelling blood back towards the heart. As a result, blood pools in the lower extremities, increasing the risk of clot formation.\r\n\r\nOther risk factors for DVT include older age, obesity, previous history of DVT, surgery, trauma, and certain medical conditions. However, in this case, the patient's recent immobility is the most significant contributing factor to the development of DVT.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 130.","responses":[{"text":"Age factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Immobilization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alcohol consumption","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15394,"text":"Which is the main site of hematopoiesis in the second trimester?","explanation":"During the second trimester of fetal development, the **spleen** serves as the main site of hematopoiesis. Hematopoiesis is the process of blood cell formation. Initially, during early embryonic development, hematopoiesis occurs in the yolk sac, then transitions to other organs as development progresses.\r\n\r\nIn the second trimester, the liver and spleen take over as the primary sites of hematopoiesis. The liver is responsible for producing red blood cells, while the spleen plays a crucial role in producing white blood cells. However, as gestation continues, hematopoiesis gradually shifts to the bone marrow, which becomes the primary site of blood cell formation after birth.\r\n\r\nThe spleen is a highly vascular organ located in the upper left side of the abdomen. Its unique architecture and blood supply make it an ideal site for hematopoiesis during the second trimester. As the fetus matures, the spleen's hematopoietic function declines, and it primarily functions as a lymphoid organ in postnatal life.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 94.","responses":[{"text":"Yolk sac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thymus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15395,"text":"What is the most underdeveloped special sense in neonates?","explanation":"The most underdeveloped special sense in neonates is **visual acuity**. At birth, the visual system of newborns is not fully matured, and their ability to see clearly and focus on objects is limited. Neonates have a visual acuity of approximately 20/200, which means they can only distinguish large, high-contrast objects at a close distance.\r\n\r\nThe immaturity of the visual system in neonates is due to the incomplete development of structures such as the retina, optic nerve, and visual cortex. The cells in the retina responsible for detailed vision, called cones, are not fully developed at birth. Additionally, the neural connections and pathways that transmit and process visual information are still developing.\r\n\r\nOver time, with visual stimulation and growth, the visual system undergoes significant maturation, and visual acuity improves. By the age of 6 months to 1 year, most infants have reached a visual acuity similar to that of adults.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 421.","responses":[{"text":"Taste","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Touch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visual acuity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hearing","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Olfaction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phonation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15632,"text":"Which of the following structures does membrane attack complex (MAC) attach to during complement system activation?","explanation":"During complement system activation, the membrane attack complex (MAC) attaches to the **lipid part of the cell membrane**. The MAC is a multi-protein complex formed as a result of complement cascade activation. It plays a crucial role in the innate immune response by directly attacking and lysing target cells, particularly bacteria and other pathogens.\r\n\r\nThe MAC is composed of several complement proteins, including C5b, C6, C7, C8, and multiple molecules of C9. These proteins assemble on the surface of the target cell to form a pore-like structure in the lipid bilayer of the cell membrane. This pore disrupts the integrity of the membrane, leading to the influx of water, ions, and other molecules into the cell. The osmotic imbalance and structural damage caused by the MAC result in cell lysis and destruction.\r\n\r\nThe attachment of the MAC to the lipid part of the cell membrane ensures its close association with the target cell and enables the subsequent formation of the pore structure that leads to cell lysis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 465.","responses":[{"text":"Lipid part of cell membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mitochondrial membrane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proteins channels on cell surface","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thin cell wall","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacteria inside cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15633,"text":"Which structure is defective in the genetic disorder Marfan syndrome?","explanation":"Marfan syndrome is a genetic disorder primarily caused by a defect in the **fibrillin-1 gene (FBN1)**. Fibrillin-1 is a glycoprotein that forms microfibrils in connective tissues, providing structural support and elasticity to various organs and tissues in the body.\r\n\r\nThe defect in FBN1 leads to the production of abnormal fibrillin-1 protein or reduced levels of functional fibrillin-1. This, in turn, affects the structure and function of connective tissues throughout the body. The most prominent manifestations of Marfan syndrome are found in the cardiovascular, musculoskeletal, and ocular systems.\r\n\r\nThe cardiovascular abnormalities in Marfan syndrome, such as aortic aneurysms and mitral valve prolapse, result from the weakened connective tissue in the blood vessels and heart valves. Skeletal abnormalities, including long limbs, joint hypermobility, and scoliosis, are also characteristic features of Marfan syndrome. Ocular manifestations, such as lens dislocation and myopia, are caused by the weakened connective tissue in the eye.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 148.","responses":[{"text":"Myelin sheath","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collagen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low-density lipoprotein (LDL) receptors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrillin-1","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15634,"text":"Complement activation leads to the formation of a membrane attack complex (MAC), which causes the lysis of the cell. By which mechanism does MAC work?","explanation":"The membrane attack complex (MAC) is a key component of the complement system that plays a crucial role in the immune response against microbes. MAC works by causing **lysis of microbes with susceptible cell membranes**.\r\n\r\nWhen complement activation occurs, a series of enzymatic reactions leads to the formation of MAC. MAC consists of several complement proteins, including C5b, C6, C7, C8, and multiple copies of C9. Once assembled, MAC forms a pore-like structure in the cell membrane of the target microbe. This pore disrupts the integrity of the cell membrane, resulting in the influx of ions and water into the microbe, leading to osmotic lysis and cell death.\r\n\r\nThe lysis of microbes by MAC is an effective defense mechanism against various pathogens, including bacteria, viruses, and some parasites. It contributes to the elimination of these microbes and helps in the resolution of infections.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 465.","responses":[{"text":"Opsonization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inducing damage to pathogen by reactive oxygen species (ROS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysis of microbes with susceptible cell membranes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibition of microbe replication","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Binding to and neutralization of bacterial toxins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15727,"text":"During leukocyte migration, the process of upregulation of selectins and integrins is referred to as which of the following?","explanation":"During leukocyte migration, the process of upregulation of selectins and integrins is referred to as **margination**. Margination is an important step in the recruitment of leukocytes from the bloodstream to the site of inflammation or infection.\r\n\r\nDuring margination, selectins and integrins are upregulated on the surface of endothelial cells lining the blood vessels. Selectins are cell adhesion molecules that mediate the initial weak interaction between leukocytes and endothelial cells. Integrins, on the other hand, are cell surface receptors that promote stronger adhesion and binding between leukocytes and endothelial cells.\r\n\r\nThe upregulation of selectins and integrins allows leukocytes to adhere to the endothelial cells and subsequently undergo diapedesis, which is the process of migrating through the blood vessel wall to reach the site of inflammation or infection.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 455.","responses":[{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adhesion cascade","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene synthesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15728,"text":"Which is not a cause of microcytic hypochromic anemia?","explanation":"**Increased red blood cell destruction** is not a cause of microcytic hypochromic anemia. Microcytic hypochromic anemia is characterized by small-sized red blood cells with reduced hemoglobin content. It is typically caused by conditions that result in impaired synthesis of hemoglobin or deficiencies in iron availability.\r\n\r\nThe common causes of microcytic hypochromic anemia include iron deficiency, which is the most common cause worldwide, and abnormalities in hemoglobin synthesis, such as thalassemias and certain sideroblastic anemias. Lead poisoning can also lead to microcytic hypochromic anemia by interfering with heme synthesis.\r\n\r\nHowever, increased red blood cell destruction, as seen in hemolytic anemias, typically results in normocytic normochromic anemia or occasionally macrocytic anemia, depending on the underlying cause. Hemolytic anemias are characterized by premature destruction of red blood cells, leading to a shorter lifespan and, in turn, compensatory mechanisms that maintain normal red blood cell size and hemoglobin content.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 411, 412, 647, 658.","responses":[{"text":"Lead poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased red blood cell destruction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mutations in the ALAS2 gene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abnormalities in hemoglobin chains","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15729,"text":"Which of the following is least likely to cause vitamin B12 deficiency?","explanation":"Among the options provided, **dietary intake** is least likely to cause vitamin B12 deficiency. Vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, is primarily obtained from animal-derived foods such as meat, fish, dairy products, and eggs. Adequate dietary intake of vitamin B12 ensures its availability for absorption in the gastrointestinal tract.\r\n\r\nOther factors listed, such as hyperthyroidism, chronic infection, cancer, and pregnancy, can contribute to vitamin B12 deficiency through different mechanisms. Hyperthyroidism may lead to malabsorption of vitamin B12 due to increased gastrointestinal motility. Chronic infections and certain cancers can disrupt the normal absorption and utilization of vitamin B12. In pregnancy, the demands for vitamin B12 increase, and inadequate intake or absorption can result in deficiency.\r\n\r\nHowever, it is important to note that although dietary intake is the least likely cause of vitamin B12 deficiency among the options provided, it can still contribute to deficiency in individuals who follow strict vegan or vegetarian diets without adequate supplementation or fortified foods.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 652.","responses":[{"text":"Pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperthyroidism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dietary intake","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cancer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15730,"text":"What protein is found in plasma, but not in serum, and can appear as a distinct band on electrophoresis that may sometimes be confused with multiple myeloma?","explanation":"The protein that is found in plasma but not in serum and can appear as a distinct band on electrophoresis, which may sometimes be confused with multiple myeloma, is **fibrinogen**.\r\n\r\nFibrinogen is a clotting protein that is present in the plasma component of blood. During the process of clotting, fibrinogen is converted to fibrin, which forms the structural framework of blood clots. In serum, which is the liquid component of blood obtained after clotting, fibrinogen is absent because it has been converted to fibrin and removed from the sample.\r\n\r\nOn electrophoresis, fibrinogen appears as a distinct band between the beta and gamma globulin regions. This band can sometimes be mistaken for the abnormal protein bands seen in multiple myeloma, a plasma cell disorder. However, differentiating between fibrinogen and abnormal proteins characteristic of multiple myeloma can be done through additional tests and clinical evaluation.","reference":"Mathew J, Sankar P, Varacallo M. Physiology, blood plasma. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed May 7, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK531504/","responses":[{"text":"Fibrinogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferrin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15887,"text":"A group of students collected data consisting of 10 variables, including 1 constant variable. Which type of chart or graph should they use to plot their data?","explanation":"The group of students should use a **bar chart** to plot their data. A bar chart is suitable for displaying categorical or discrete data, where each variable is represented by a separate bar. In this case, since the students have collected 10 variables, a bar chart can effectively present the data.\r\n\r\nA bar chart consists of a series of bars, with each bar representing a different variable. The length or height of each bar corresponds to the frequency or count of that variable. The constant variable can be represented by a separate bar that remains the same height or length across all variables.\r\n\r\nUsing a bar chart allows the students to compare the values of each variable visually and easily identify any patterns or differences. It is particularly useful when presenting data that is not continuous or when there is a small number of variables.","reference":"Charts for three or more variables in predictive analytics| syncfusion. Accessed May 21, 2023. https://help.syncfusion.com/predictive-analytics/charts-for-three-or-more-variables","responses":[{"text":"Histogram","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scatter Plot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Line Graph","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pie Chart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bar Chart","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15888,"text":"A child gets a micro-cut on his finger while playing with a razor. The wound stops bleeding shortly after. Which of the following mechanisms is primarily responsible for this?","explanation":"The primary mechanism responsible for the cessation of bleeding in the child's micro-cut wound is **platelet plug formation**. Platelets, also known as thrombocytes, are small cell fragments in the blood that play a crucial role in hemostasis. When a blood vessel is injured, platelets adhere to the exposed collagen in the damaged vessel wall. This adhesion is facilitated by von Willebrand factor and other adhesive molecules.\r\n\r\nOnce adhered, platelets become activated and undergo shape change, releasing granules containing various substances such as ADP and thromboxane A2. These substances further recruit and activate more platelets, leading to the formation of a platelet plug at the site of injury. The platelet plug acts as a temporary seal to prevent further blood loss from the injured vessel.\r\n\r\nWhile vasoconstriction, the intrinsic and extrinsic pathways of coagulation, and fibrin formation are also important components of hemostasis, in the context of the child's micro-cut wound, platelet plug formation is the primary mechanism responsible for stopping the bleeding.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 478.","responses":[{"text":"Extrinsic pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasoconstriction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrinsic pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fibrin formation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Platelet plug formation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15900,"text":"An elderly man presents with chronic abdominal pain and an enlarged spleen. Which disease is most likely responsible for his symptoms?","explanation":"The most likely disease responsible for the elderly man's symptoms of chronic abdominal pain and an enlarged spleen is a **myeloproliferative disorder**. Myeloproliferative disorders are a group of hematological conditions characterized by the excessive production of blood cells in the bone marrow. These disorders can affect various blood cell lineages, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.\r\n\r\nIn the context of the symptoms described, an enlarged spleen (splenomegaly) is a common finding in myeloproliferative disorders. The abnormal proliferation of blood cells leads to increased workload on the spleen, resulting in its enlargement. The chronic abdominal pain may be associated with the splenomegaly.\r\n\r\nOther features commonly observed in myeloproliferative disorders include elevated white blood cell or platelet counts, bone marrow fibrosis, and potential transformation into acute leukemia. Specific subtypes of myeloproliferative disorders include polycythemia vera, essential thrombocythemia, and primary myelofibrosis.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 622-627.","responses":[{"text":"von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic autoimmune hemolytic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemophilia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Myeloproliferative disorder","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15904,"text":"What type of graph is most likely to show a left and right skewed curve?","explanation":"A **histogram** is most likely to show a left or right skewed curve. A histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution of data, where the data is divided into intervals or bins along the x-axis, and the frequency or count of observations falling within each bin is represented on the y-axis.\r\n\r\nA left skewed (negative skewed) curve occurs when the tail of the distribution extends towards the left side, indicating a higher frequency of lower values. This typically happens when there are a few extremely high values that pull the mean towards the higher end, resulting in a longer left tail.\r\n\r\nA right skewed (positive skewed) curve occurs when the tail of the distribution extends towards the right side, indicating a higher frequency of higher values. This typically happens when there are a few extremely low values that pull the mean towards the lower end, resulting in a longer right tail.\r\n\r\nHistograms are useful for visualizing the shape and distribution of data, particularly when dealing with continuous or discrete numerical variables.","reference":"1.3.3.14.6. Histogram Interpretation: Skewed (Non-normal) Right. Accessed May 21, 2023. https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section3/histogr6.htm","responses":[{"text":"Pie chart","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Line graph","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scatter plot","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histogram","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Box plot","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15912,"text":"Proteolysis of which of the following components is a critical step during complement activation?","explanation":"During complement activation, proteolysis of **C3** is a critical step. The complement system consists of a group of proteins that work together to enhance the immune response and eliminate pathogens. C3 is a central component of the complement cascade.\r\n\r\nActivation of the complement system can occur through different pathways, including the classical pathway, alternative pathway, and lectin pathway. Regardless of the pathway involved, all of them converge on the proteolysis of C3.\r\n\r\nWhen C3 is proteolytically cleaved, it generates two fragments: C3a and C3b. C3a is an anaphylatoxin that induces inflammation and recruits immune cells to the site of infection or injury. C3b, on the other hand, plays a crucial role in opsonization, where it binds to the surface of pathogens and enhances their recognition and phagocytosis by immune cells.\r\n\r\nThe cleavage of C3 triggers a cascade of events leading to the formation of the membrane attack complex (MAC) and subsequent lysis of the pathogen.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 465.","responses":[{"text":"C4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"C5","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15929,"text":"A young female patient presents to the outpatient department with complaints of bleeding and rashes on her body. On physical examination, she has petechiae on her body, and laboratory findings show low platelets with megakaryocytes. Prothrombin time (PT) and activated partial thrombin time (aPTT) are in a normal range. Which of the following condition does she most likely have?","explanation":"Based on the clinical presentation and laboratory findings, the most likely condition for this young female patient is **idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)**. ITP is an autoimmune disorder characterized by a decrease in platelet count, leading to easy bruising, petechiae, and mucosal bleeding.\r\n\r\nThe presence of petechiae and low platelet count suggests abnormal platelet function or destruction. In ITP, there is an immune-mediated destruction of platelets, resulting in their decreased lifespan. Megakaryocytes, the precursor cells of platelets, are typically increased in the bone marrow as the body tries to compensate for the reduced platelet count.\r\n\r\nThe normal PT and aPTT indicate that the patient's coagulation factors are functioning properly, ruling out other causes of bleeding disorders such as deficiencies in clotting factors or vitamin K deficiency.\r\n\r\nFurther diagnostic tests, such as assessing platelet antibodies and ruling out other potential causes of thrombocytopenia, may be performed to confirm the diagnosis of ITP.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 664-665.","responses":[{"text":"von Willebrand disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Megaloblastic anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia minor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin K deficiency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15930,"text":"An 18-year-old complains of fatigue and shortness of breath. Her mean corpuscular volume (MCV) is 60 femtolitre and her mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) is 22 picogram. Which of the following is true for the morphology of her red blood cells?","explanation":"The given values of mean corpuscular volume (MCV) and mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) indicate **microcytic and hypochromic** red blood cells. Microcytic red blood cells are smaller than normal, and hypochromic cells have reduced hemoglobin content.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the MCV of 60 femtoliters indicates microcytosis, as it falls below the normal range. The MCH of 22 picograms indicates hypochromia, as it is below the normal range for hemoglobin content. Together, these findings suggest a microcytic hypochromic anemia.\r\n\r\nMicrocytic hypochromic anemia is commonly associated with iron deficiency, the most common cause of anemia worldwide. Iron deficiency can result from inadequate dietary intake, malabsorption, increased demand, or chronic blood loss. It leads to decreased production of hemoglobin and smaller, paler red blood cells.\r\n\r\nFurther diagnostic tests, such as iron studies and evaluation of iron stores, may be needed to confirm the underlying cause of the microcytic hypochromic anemia and guide appropriate treatment.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 635, 637.","responses":[{"text":"Microcytic normochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Macrocytic normochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Normocytic normochromic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Microcytic hypochromic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Normocytic hypochromic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15931,"text":"Which plasma protein is commonly measured to indicate infection or inflammation?","explanation":"**C-reactive protein (CRP)** is a plasma protein that is commonly measured to indicate the presence of infection or inflammation. It is an acute-phase reactant, meaning its levels increase rapidly in response to tissue injury, infection, or inflammation.\r\n\r\nCRP is produced by the liver in response to cytokines, particularly interleukin-6 (IL-6), which is released during the early stages of inflammation. Its levels in the blood rise within a few hours of the onset of inflammation and can increase significantly.\r\n\r\nMeasuring CRP levels can be helpful in diagnosing and monitoring various conditions, including bacterial and viral infections, autoimmune disorders, and cardiovascular diseases. Elevated CRP levels indicate the presence and severity of inflammation, while a decrease in CRP levels indicates a response to treatment or resolution of the underlying condition.\r\n\r\nCRP is measured using high-sensitivity CRP (hs-CRP) assays, which can detect even low levels of CRP and provide valuable information about the inflammatory state of the patient.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 102.","responses":[{"text":"Immunoglobulins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Complement proteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C-reactive protein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coagulation factors","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15932,"text":"Which of the following is released from granulocytes in an allergic reaction?","explanation":"**Histamine** is released from granulocytes, specifically mast cells and basophils, during an allergic reaction. Histamine is stored in granules within these cells and is released in response to an allergen or an immune trigger.\r\n\r\nOnce released, histamine acts on various target tissues and cells, leading to the characteristic symptoms of an allergic reaction. It causes vasodilation and increased vascular permeability, leading to local tissue swelling, redness, and heat. Histamine also stimulates the nerve endings, causing itching and pain.\r\n\r\nIn addition to its effects on blood vessels and nerves, histamine plays a role in the immune response by attracting other immune cells to the site of inflammation and promoting the release of other inflammatory mediators. It can also stimulate the production of more histamine, further amplifying the allergic response.\r\n\r\nAntihistamines are commonly used to alleviate symptoms of allergies by blocking the effects of histamine on target tissues.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 469-470.","responses":[{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interleukin-1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotrienes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IgE antibody","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15933,"text":"Which of the following mechanisms attracts leukocytes toward the site of infection?","explanation":"**Chemotaxis** is the mechanism that attracts leukocytes towards the site of infection. It is a process by which leukocytes are guided towards a specific location in response to chemical signals released by cells at the site of inflammation or infection. These chemical signals, known as chemotactic factors or chemokines, act as attractants for leukocytes, helping them migrate from the bloodstream to the affected tissues.\r\n\r\nChemotaxis plays a crucial role in the immune response by directing the movement of leukocytes, such as neutrophils and macrophages, towards the site of infection or tissue damage. It allows the immune cells to target and eliminate pathogens, clear cellular debris, and initiate the inflammatory response.\r\n\r\nThe process of chemotaxis involves leukocytes sensing and responding to concentration gradients of chemotactic factors. This directional movement is facilitated by the rearrangement of the cell's cytoskeleton, allowing the leukocytes to migrate towards higher concentrations of chemotactic factors.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 451.","responses":[{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Inflammation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Opsonization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15934,"text":"Which disease occurs when the hydrophilic amino acid glutamic acid is replaced by the hydrophobic amino acid valine at position 6 in the globin chain?","explanation":"The replacement of glutamic acid with valine at position 6 in the globin chain of hemoglobin results in the condition known as **sickle cell anemia**. This amino acid substitution is caused by a point mutation in the β-globin gene. The abnormal hemoglobin molecule, called hemoglobin S (HbS), has a tendency to polymerize under certain conditions, leading to the characteristic sickle shape of red blood cells.\r\n\r\nThe polymerization of HbS causes red blood cells to become rigid and less flexible, resulting in their abnormal sickle shape. These sickled red blood cells can obstruct blood vessels, leading to impaired blood flow and tissue ischemia. This can cause a wide range of complications, including chronic hemolytic anemia, vaso-occlusive crises, organ damage, and increased susceptibility to infections.\r\n\r\nSickle cell anemia follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, meaning that individuals must inherit two copies of the mutated β-globin gene (one from each parent) to develop the disease. Heterozygous carriers (those with one normal and one mutated β-globin gene) may exhibit some resistance to malaria, which is believed to contribute to the persistence of the sickle cell gene in certain populations.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 641.","responses":[{"text":"Hemophilia A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell anemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin C disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Beta-thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cystic fibrosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15935,"text":"Which chromosome is affected in β-thalassemia?","explanation":"**β-thalassemia** is primarily caused by mutations in the β-globin gene, which is located on **chromosome 11**. The β-globin gene is responsible for producing the β-globin subunit of hemoglobin, a protein that is essential for normal red blood cell function. Mutations in the β-globin gene can result in reduced or absent production of β-globin chains, leading to an imbalance in the production of α- and β-globin chains.\r\n\r\nThe imbalance in globin chain production disrupts the formation of normal hemoglobin molecules, leading to ineffective erythropoiesis and the production of abnormal red blood cells. This can result in various clinical manifestations, including anemia and a range of complications associated with chronic hemolysis.\r\n\r\nThe inheritance of β-thalassemia is autosomal recessive, meaning that an individual needs to inherit two copies of the mutated β-globin gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. Heterozygous carriers (individuals with one normal and one mutated β-globin gene) are generally asymptomatic but can transmit the condition to their offspring.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 644.","responses":[{"text":"Chromosome18","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromososme 9","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromosome 16","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromososme 17","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromosome 11","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15955,"text":"Which of the following is the genetic inheritance of hemophilia A?","explanation":"**Hemophilia A** is inherited in an X-linked recessive manner. This means that the gene mutation responsible for hemophilia A is located on the X chromosome. Since males have one X and one Y chromosome, a mutation in the single X chromosome they inherit from their mother can result in the expression of the disease. Females, on the other hand, have two X chromosomes, and the presence of a normal copy of the gene on one X chromosome can compensate for the mutated copy on the other.\r\n\r\nAs a result of the X-linked recessive inheritance, hemophilia A primarily affects males, while females are typically carriers of the condition. Male individuals who inherit the mutated gene will have hemophilia A, while female carriers have a 50% chance of passing the mutated gene to their offspring.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that in rare cases, females can also be affected by hemophilia A if they inherit the mutated gene on both X chromosomes or if they inherit the mutation along with other genetic factors.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 668.","responses":[{"text":"X-linked dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"X-linked recessive","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal dominant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autosomal recessive","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is not a genetic disorder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15956,"text":"Which vitamin is required for the conversion of 5-methyl-tetrahydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate in the conversion of homocysteine to methionine?","explanation":"**Vitamin B12**, also known as cobalamin, is required for the conversion of **5-methyl-tetrahydrofolate** to tetrahydrofolate during the conversion of homocysteine to methionine. This enzymatic reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme methionine synthase.\r\n\r\nVitamin B12 plays a crucial role in one-carbon metabolism, which involves the transfer of methyl groups for various biochemical reactions, including DNA synthesis and the formation of methionine, an essential amino acid. In the conversion of homocysteine to methionine, methyl groups derived from 5-methyl-tetrahydrofolate are transferred to homocysteine with the help of vitamin B12.\r\n\r\nDeficiency of vitamin B12 can lead to impaired methionine synthesis and an increase in homocysteine levels, which is associated with various health problems, including megaloblastic anemia and neurological disorders.","reference":"Murray RK, Bender D, Botham KM, Kennelly PJ. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 29th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2012: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Vitamin B6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin C","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin A","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vitamin B9","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15957,"text":"If the set point for diabetes mellitus in a population was 105 mg/dL and the researcher dropped it to 100 mg/dL. What will be the change in sensitivity and specificity?","explanation":"In the context of diagnostic testing, sensitivity and specificity are measures of the test's performance in correctly identifying individuals with a particular condition and correctly identifying individuals without the condition, respectively.\r\n\r\nIf the **set point** for diabetes mellitus is **lowered** from 105 mg/dL to 100 mg/dL, it means that the threshold for diagnosing diabetes has become **more stringent**. This change will lead to an **increase in sensitivity** and a **decrease in specificity**.\r\n\r\n**Sensitivity** is the ability of a test to correctly identify individuals who have the disease (true positive rate). By lowering the threshold, some individuals who were previously considered negative for diabetes may now be classified as positive, increasing sensitivity.\r\n\r\n**Specificity** is the ability of a test to correctly identify individuals who do not have the disease (true negative rate). With a more stringent cutoff, individuals without diabetes who previously fell below the threshold may now be classified as (false) positive, leading to a decrease in specificity.","reference":"Trevethan R. Sensitivity, specificity, and predictive values: foundations, pliabilities, and pitfalls in research and practice. Frontiers in Public Health. 2017;5. Accessed May 26, 2023. https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpubh.2017.00307","responses":[{"text":"Only sensitivity decreases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensitivity increases but specificity decreases","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"No change in sensitivity or specificity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only sensitivity increases","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sensitivity decreases but specificity increases","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15958,"text":"Which of the following is considered negative reinforcement?","explanation":"**Negative reinforcement** refers to the **removal or avoidance of an aversive or unpleasant stimulus in order to encourage the repetition of a particular behavior**. \r\n\r\nNegative reinforcement works by increasing the likelihood of a behavior by removing or avoiding a negative consequence or stimulus. When a behavior leads to the removal of a painful or aversive situation, it strengthens the association between the behavior and the desired outcome, making it more likely to be repeated in the future.\r\n\r\nIt is important to note that negative reinforcement is different from punishment, which involves the application of aversive stimuli to discourage a behavior. Negative reinforcement, on the other hand, involves the removal or avoidance of aversive stimuli to encourage a behavior. Both negative reinforcement and punishment can influence behavior, but they operate through different mechanisms.","reference":"Negative reinforcement: definition, examples, and more. Psych Central. Published December 4, 2019. Accessed May 26, 2023. https://psychcentral.com/health/what-is-negative-reinforcement-definition-3-types-and-examples","responses":[{"text":"Reward prevents the repetition of behavior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Punishment will prevent the repetition of behaviour","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Removal of painful situations will encourage the repetition of behavior","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"An upleasant stimulus encourages the repetition of behavior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Removal of reward prevents the repetition of behavior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15959,"text":"In which of the following forms is dietary folate present?","explanation":"Dietary folate is present in the form of **polyglutamate**. Folate, also known as vitamin B9, is a water-soluble vitamin that plays a crucial role in various cellular processes, including DNA synthesis and cell division. In its natural form, folate is found in foods as a polyglutamate molecule, meaning it is composed of multiple glutamate units. The polyglutamate form is biologically inactive and needs to undergo enzymatic cleavage in the intestinal mucosa to yield monoglutamate, the active form of folate.\r\n\r\nOnce absorbed into the bloodstream, monoglutamate folate can be transported to various tissues and cells where it is utilized in essential metabolic reactions. The polyglutamate form of folate found in dietary sources helps to ensure its stability and bioavailability. It is worth noting that during the digestion and absorption process, dietary polyglutamate folate is converted into monoglutamate form before it can be efficiently utilized by the body.","reference":"Murray RK, Victor WR, Bender D, Kathleen MB, Weil PA, Kennelly PJ. Harper’s Illustrated Biochemistry. 28th ed. McGraw-Hill Professional; 2009: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Monoglutamate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monoaspartate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monosulfate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyglutamate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyaspartate","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15960,"text":"Which of the following represents the clinicopathological representation of Arthus reaction?","explanation":"**Arthus reaction** is a type III hypersensitivity reaction characterized by immune complex deposition and subsequent inflammation in tissues. The classic clinicopathological representation of Arthus reaction is **cutaneous vasculitis**. This is characterized by inflammation of the blood vessels in the skin, resulting in skin lesions such as erythema, edema, and necrosis. The reaction occurs when pre-existing antibodies in the circulation encounter antigens locally at the site of inflammation, leading to immune complex formation and subsequent activation of the complement system and recruitment of inflammatory cells.\r\n\r\nThe immune complexes deposit in the small blood vessels of the skin, triggering an inflammatory response. The resulting vasculitis leads to the characteristic cutaneous manifestations. It is important to note that Arthus reaction is a localized immune complex-mediated hypersensitivity reaction, primarily affecting the skin. It is distinct from systemic vasculitis, which involves inflammation of blood vessels in multiple organs. Other manifestations such as nephritis and acute arthritis are not typically associated with Arthus reaction, making cutaneous vasculitis the hallmark of this specific hypersensitivity response.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 211.","responses":[{"text":"Cutaneous vasculitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic vasculitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nephritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin lesions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15961,"text":"Leucocytes reach the inflamed tissue by which of the following process?","explanation":"During inflammation, leukocytes (white blood cells) must leave the bloodstream and migrate to the site of tissue injury or infection. This process is known as **diapedesis** or extravasation.\r\n\r\nDiapedesis involves several steps. First, leukocytes undergo a process called rolling, where they loosely adhere to the endothelial cells lining the blood vessels. This rolling is mediated by selectins and their ligands. Chemotactic factors released at the site of inflammation then attract the leukocytes towards the inflamed tissue, a process known as chemotaxis.\r\n\r\nNext, the leukocytes marginate, meaning they move towards the periphery of the blood vessels. This occurs due to the slower flow of blood in the microvasculature, allowing leukocytes to move closer to the endothelial cells.\r\n\r\nFinally, the leukocytes undergo diapedesis, which involves their migration through the endothelial cells and basement membrane of blood vessels. This allows them to enter the inflamed tissue and actively participate in the immune response.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 78.","responses":[{"text":"Chemotaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoeboid movement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Margination","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rolling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diapedesis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15962,"text":"Which of the following is a type II hypersensitivity reaction?","explanation":"A **type II hypersensitivity reaction**, also known as cytotoxic hypersensitivity, occurs when antibodies bind to antigens present on the surface of cells or tissues, leading to their destruction by various mechanisms. One example of a type II hypersensitivity reaction is **myasthenia gravis**.\r\n\r\nMyasthenia gravis is an autoimmune disorder characterized by muscle weakness and fatigue. In this condition, autoantibodies, specifically IgG antibodies, target and bind to acetylcholine receptors (AChRs) located on the postsynaptic membrane of neuromuscular junctions. This binding interferes with the normal transmission of nerve impulses to muscle fibers, resulting in muscle weakness.\r\n\r\nThe binding of autoantibodies to AChRs can activate complement cascade and recruit immune cells, leading to the destruction of AChRs and impairment of neuromuscular function.\r\n\r\nOther examples of type II hypersensitivity reactions include autoimmune hemolytic anemia, immune thrombocytopenia, and certain drug-induced immune reactions.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 210.","responses":[{"text":"Serum sickness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 diabetes mellitus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchial asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mysthania gravis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15963,"text":"Where are hemangioblasts formed?","explanation":"**Hemangioblasts** are formed in the **mesoderm** during embryonic development. The mesoderm is one of the three primary germ layers in the developing embryo, responsible for giving rise to various tissues and organs, including the circulatory system.\r\n\r\nHemangioblasts are precursor cells that have the capacity to differentiate into both blood cells and blood vessels. They are considered bipotential progenitors, capable of generating hematopoietic stem cells (which give rise to blood cells) as well as angioblasts (which form blood vessels).\r\n\r\nDuring embryogenesis, hemangioblasts arise from mesodermal cells in specific regions called the blood islands. These blood islands are found in the yolk sac, the first site of blood cell and blood vessel formation in the developing embryo.\r\n\r\nAs development progresses, hemangioblasts migrate to other regions and contribute to the formation of blood cells and blood vessels throughout the body.","reference":"Sadler TW, Langman J. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 12th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2011: 75.","responses":[{"text":"Liver","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Yolk sac","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15964,"text":"A 65-year-old man presented to the outpatient department with complaints of cough and fever. He was diagnosed with acute respiratory infection/inflammation. On a complete blood picture (CBC) test, which of the following leukocyte will be most abundant?","explanation":"**Neutrophils** are a type of granulocyte and play a critical role in the early stages of the immune response to bacterial and fungal infections.\r\n\r\nNeutrophils are mobilized from the bone marrow and recruited to the site of infection in response to inflammatory signals. They are highly phagocytic and capable of engulfing and destroying pathogens. The increased presence of neutrophils in the blood is known as neutrophilia.\r\n\r\nIn acute respiratory infections, such as pneumonia or bronchitis, neutrophils are recruited to the respiratory tract to combat invading microorganisms. The increased number of neutrophils in the blood is a reflection of the body's immune response to the infection.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 96.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15965,"text":"Which one of the following substances is required to dissolve the fibrin clot to achieve normal blood flow?","explanation":"To achieve normal blood flow, the fibrin clot needs to be dissolved, a process known as fibrinolysis. **Plasmin**, an enzyme, is primarily responsible for breaking down the fibrin clot and restoring blood flow.\r\n\r\nPlasmin is derived from its inactive precursor plasminogen through the action of tissue plasminogen activator (tPA) and urokinase-type plasminogen activator (uPA). These activators convert plasminogen into plasmin, which then degrades the fibrin meshwork of the clot. Plasmin breaks down fibrin into smaller fragments called fibrin degradation products (FDPs).\r\n\r\nSeveral factors, including tPA, uPA, and other cofactors, regulate the activation of plasminogen and ensure a controlled and localized fibrinolysis process. The fibrinolytic system is essential in maintaining blood flow, preventing excessive clot formation, and promoting the resolution of blood clots once they have served their purpose.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 484.","responses":[{"text":"Antithrombin III","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Heparin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thrombin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminocaproic acid","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15966,"text":"In which of the following conditions does iron undergo oxidation from ferrous to the ferric form in hemoglobin?","explanation":"In **methemoglobinemia**, iron in hemoglobin undergoes oxidation from the ferrous (Fe2+) form to the ferric (Fe3+) form. This conversion alters the binding affinity of hemoglobin for oxygen, resulting in impaired oxygen delivery to the tissues.\r\n\r\nMethemoglobinemia can be inherited or acquired. Inherited forms may result from genetic mutations affecting the enzyme systems responsible for maintaining iron in the reduced state, such as cytochrome b5 reductase or hemoglobin M. Acquired methemoglobinemia can be caused by exposure to certain drugs, chemicals, or toxins that oxidize hemoglobin.\r\n\r\nThe conversion of ferrous iron to ferric iron in methemoglobin prevents oxygen binding to hemoglobin, leading to a functional impairment of the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. The affected individuals may exhibit cyanosis (bluish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes) due to the increased presence of methemoglobin.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 637.","responses":[{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thalassemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycythemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methemoglobinemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sickle cell disease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15967,"text":"Stages of child development were given by which of the following scientists?","explanation":"The stages of child development were given by **Erik Erikson**, a prominent developmental psychologist. Erikson proposed a psychosocial theory of development that encompasses the entire lifespan, but his theory is particularly well-known for its focus on childhood and adolescence.\r\n\r\nErikson's theory outlines eight stages of psychosocial development, each characterized by a specific conflict or challenge that individuals must navigate in order to develop a healthy sense of self and a positive relationship with the social environment. These stages span from infancy to old age and cover various aspects of development, including trust versus mistrust, autonomy versus shame and doubt, initiative versus guilt, industry versus inferiority, identity versus role confusion, intimacy versus isolation, generativity versus stagnation, and integrity versus despair.","reference":"Orenstein GA, Lewis L. Eriksons stages of psychosocial development. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed May 28, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556096/","responses":[{"text":"Sigmund Freud","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jean Paiget","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lawrence Kohlberg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lev Vygotsky","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erik Erikson","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15968,"text":"In which location does a saddle embolus usually lodge?","explanation":"A saddle embolus typically lodges in the pulmonary artery. The **pulmonary artery** is the blood vessel that carries deoxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs for oxygenation. When a saddle embolus occurs, it means that a blood clot, known as an embolus, becomes lodged at the point where the pulmonary artery splits into two branches, resembling a saddle. This obstruction can severely impede or block blood flow to the lungs, leading to potentially life-threatening consequences.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 131.","responses":[{"text":"At the aortic arch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the coronary artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the superior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the bifurcation of the pulmonary artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"At the carotid artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

